ment": "(added \"Voices From Within\" section)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sing_Sing"}
{"title_page": "Lena, Lady Login", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Lena Login\n| image       = Lena Login from a miniature by Fisher, 1850.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = [[Lena Login]] from a miniature by Fisher, 1850\n| birth_name  = Lena Campbell\n| birth_date  = 1820\n| birth_place = [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]]\n| death_date  = April 17, 1904\n| death_place = [[Aylesford]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =\n| spouse      = [[John Spencer Login|Sir John Spencer Login]]\n| partner     =\n| children    = six\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[Scotland]]\n}}\n'''Lady Login, Lena Login''' (born '''Lena Campbell'''; 1820 \u2013 April 17, 1904) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] courtier and author. She was involved with educating [[Duleep Singh]] and bringing him to the UK. She was asked by Queen Victoria to look after an Indian noble and to find her an acceptable husband.\n\n==Life==\nLogin was born in [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]] in Scotland in 1820.\n\nShe went to India with her sister and brother-in-law, Major Hope Dick.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Login|first=Lady|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZK3ix0VFzeAC&pg=PA67&lpg=PA67&dq=%22Major+Hope+Dick%22&source=bl&ots=nvh2QF6aiy&sig=ACfU3U2hG5HGyeGf1erYi5xS3cywsbMmQA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjGpcWnzcDoAhWYaRUIHaZEDTsQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Major%20Hope%20Dick%22&f=false|title=Sir John Login and Duleep Singh|last2=Malleson|first2=Col G. B.|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distri|language=en}}</ref> It was in Lucknow that she married [[John Spencer Login]] in 1842.<ref name=blogbl>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.bl.uk/asian-and-african/2017/07/children-of-sir-john-spencer-login-in-lucknow-in-1846.html|title=Children of Sir John Spencer Login in Lucknow in 1846 - Asian and African studies blog|website=blogs.bl.uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> He was the Resident Surgeon at [[Lucknow]], the physician to the court of Oudh and [[Postmaster General]] of Oudh.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\"/>\n[[File:The Children of Sir John Spencer Login in Lucknow, anon, 1846.png|left|thumb|''The Children of Sir John Spencer Login in Lucknow'', anon. Miniature on ivory, 1846.<ref name=blogbl/>]]\nAs physician to the Court of Oudh, Login was barred from directly examining women in the [[zenana]].<ref name=\"Login1890\">{{cite book|last=Login|first=Lena Campbell|title=Sir John Login and Duleep Singh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZK3ix0VFzeAC&pg=PR14|year=1890|publisher=Normal Publishers and Distributors|location=New Delhi|pages=1\u201314|id=}}</ref> However, here, his wife Lena was able assist in diagnosing the medical conditions.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\" />\n\nTheir children were depicted in a miniature on ivory by an anonymous Indian artist in 1846. The scene shows their oldest son Edward William Spencer Login (born 1843) on a rocking horse, their daughter Lena Margaret Campbell Login (1845) in a blue dress, and the infant Louisa Marion d\u2019Arcy Login (1846) held by the children's [[Amah (occupation)|ayah]]. She and the Indian child in the picture are unidentified.<ref name=blogbl/> They had six children.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48644/version/0 Login (n\u00e9e Campbell), Lena, Lady Login.] Rosemary Cargill Raza, ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Oxford University Press, Oxford. Online edition. Retrieved 14 June 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn 1849 her husband was made the guardian to [[Duleep Singh]] who was a deposed teenage ruler. Lena became part of his education giving him lessons in expected (British) behaviour. Duleep Singh became a Christian in 1853 and the following year they all went to Britain where her husband was knighted.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\"/>\n\nIn 1858 Queen Victoria asked her to find a suitor for her god daughter, [[Victoria Gouramma]]. There was an expectation that she would be a suitable wife for [[Duleep Singh]] was an deposed member of royalty, but he announced that he intended to marry an English woman. Lady Login tried to find a suitable European noble to become Gowramma's husband, but Gowramma married Lt. Col. John Campbell, who was 30 years older than her, despite the schemes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48644;jsessionid=6D7C1816A6273255CAEB1FFFD51DC683|title=Login [n\u00e9e Campbell], Lena, Lady Login (1820\u20131904), courtier|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48644|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nLogin died in [[Aylesford]] in 1904.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Login, Lena}}\n[[Category:1820 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Scotland]]\n[[Category:Courtiers]]\n[[Category:Wives of knights]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Lena Login\n| image       = Lena Login from a miniature by Fisher, 1850.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     = [[Lena Login]] from a miniature by Fisher, 1850\n| birth_name  = Lena Campbell\n| birth_date  = 1820\n| birth_place = [[Perth]]\n| death_date  = April 17, 1904\n| death_place = [[Aylesford]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =\n| spouse      = [[John Spencer Login|Sir John Spencer Login]]\n| partner     =\n| children    = six\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n| footnotes   =\n| nationality = [[Scotland]]\n}}\n'''Lady Login, Lena Login''' (born '''Lena Campbell'''; 1820 \u2013 April 17, 1904) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] courtier and author. She was involved with educating [[Duleep Singh]] and bringing him to the UK. She was asked by Queen Victoria to look after an Indian noble and to find her an acceptable husband.\n\n==Life==\nLogin was born in [[Perth]] in Scotland in 1820.\n\nShe went to India with her sister and brother-in-law, Major Hope Dick.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Login|first=Lady|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZK3ix0VFzeAC&pg=PA67&lpg=PA67&dq=%22Major+Hope+Dick%22&source=bl&ots=nvh2QF6aiy&sig=ACfU3U2hG5HGyeGf1erYi5xS3cywsbMmQA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjGpcWnzcDoAhWYaRUIHaZEDTsQ6AEwAXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Major%20Hope%20Dick%22&f=false|title=Sir John Login and Duleep Singh|last2=Malleson|first2=Col G. B.|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distri|language=en}}</ref> It was in Lucknow that she married [[John Spencer Login]] in 1842.<ref name=blogbl>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.bl.uk/asian-and-african/2017/07/children-of-sir-john-spencer-login-in-lucknow-in-1846.html|title=Children of Sir John Spencer Login in Lucknow in 1846 - Asian and African studies blog|website=blogs.bl.uk|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> He was the Resident Surgeon at [[Lucknow]], the physician to the court of Oudh and [[Postmaster General]] of Oudh.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\"/>\n[[File:The Children of Sir John Spencer Login in Lucknow, anon, 1846.png|left|thumb|''The Children of Sir John Spencer Login in Lucknow'', anon. Miniature on ivory, 1846.<ref name=blogbl/>]]\nAs physician to the Court of Oudh, Login was barred from directly examining women in the [[zenana]].<ref name=\"Login1890\">{{cite book|last=Login|first=Lena Campbell|title=Sir John Login and Duleep Singh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZK3ix0VFzeAC&pg=PR14|year=1890|publisher=Normal Publishers and Distributors|location=New Delhi|page=1\u201314|id=}}</ref> However, here, his wife Lena was able assist in diagnosing the medical conditions.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\" />\n\nTheir children were depicted in a miniature on ivory by an anonymous Indian artist in 1846. The scene shows their oldest son Edward William Spencer Login (born 1843) on a rocking horse, their daughter Lena Margaret Campbell Login (1845) in a blue dress, and the infant Louisa Marion d\u2019Arcy Login (1846) held by the children's [[Amah (occupation)|ayah]]. She and the Indian child in the picture are unidentified.<ref name=blogbl/> They had six children.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\">[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48644/version/0 Login (n\u00e9e Campbell), Lena, Lady Login.] Rosemary Cargill Raza, ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Oxford University Press, Oxford. Online edition. Retrieved 14 June 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1849 her husband was made the guardian to [[Duleep Singh]] who was a deposed teenage ruler. Lena became part of his education giving him lessons in expected (British) behaviour. Duleep Singh became a Christian in 1853 and the following year they all went to Britain where her husband was knighted.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\"/>\n\nIn 1858 Queen Victoria asked her to find a suitor for her god daughter, [[Victoria Gouramma]]. There was an expectation that she would be a suitable wife for [[Duleep Singh]] was an deposed member of royalty, but he announced that he intended to marry an English woman. Lady Login tried to find a suitable European noble to become Gowramma's husband, but Gowramma married Lt. Col. John Campbell, who was 30 years older than her, despite the schemes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-48644;jsessionid=6D7C1816A6273255CAEB1FFFD51DC683|title=Login [n\u00e9e Campbell], Lena, Lady Login (1820\u20131904), courtier|website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|language=en|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/48644|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nLogin died in [[Aylesford]] in 1904.<ref name=\"Lenaoxfordbio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Login, Lena}}\n[[Category:1820 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Perth, Scotland]]\n[[Category:Courtiers]]\n[[Category:Wives of knights]]\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix placename links, replaced:Perth\u2192Perth(2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lena,_Lady_Login"}
{"title_page": "K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name =K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol\n| title =Ajaw of [[Tikal]]<br/>13th in the line\n| image =K'inich Muwaan Jol.svg\n| image_size =150px\n| caption =K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol's glyph\n| reign =?-359\n| coronation =\n| full name = \n| predecessor =[[Unen Bahlam]]\n| successor =[[Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I]]\n| spouse  =\n| issue =Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I\n| royal house =\n| father =\n| mother =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =May 23, 359?\n| death_place =\n| date of burial =\n| place of burial =\n| religion     =[[Maya religion]] \n|}}\n'''K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol''',<ref group=\"N\">The ruler's name, when transcribed is '''K\u02bcINICH-[MUWAN]JOL''', translated \"Radiant Hawk Skull\", Martin & Grube 2008, p.27.</ref> (died 359) was ''[[ajaw]]'' of the [[maya civilization|Maya]] city-state of [[Tikal]]. He was father of Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I and he ruled until 359.<ref>Martin & Grube 2008, p.27.</ref><ref group=\"N\">These are the dates indicated on the Maya inscriptions in [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar]], Death: 8.16.2.6.0 11 Ajaw 13 Pop, Martin & Grube 2008, p.27</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}<!--BEGIN biblio format. If indent param. is used,  Pls use a colon (:) instead of asterisk (*) for bullet markers in the references list -->\n:{{cite book|author=Martin, Simon|authorlink=Simon Martin (Mayanist)|author2=[[Nikolai Grube]]|year=2008|title=Chronicle of the Maya Kings and Queens: Deciphering the Dynasties of the Ancient Maya|location=London and New York|publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]]|edition=2nd|isbn=9780500287262|oclc=191753193}}\n{{refend}}<!-- END biblio format style -->\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Rulers of Tikal|''Ajaw'' of Tikal]]|before=[[Unen Bahlam]]|after=[[Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I]]|years=?-359}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Tikal}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol}}\n[[Category:Rulers of Tikal]]\n[[Category:4th century in the Maya civilization]]\n[[Category:4th-century monarchs in North America]]\n[[Category:359 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Mesoamerica-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name =K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol\n| title =Ajaw of [[Tikal]]<br/>13th in the line\n| image =K'inich Muwaan Jol.svg\n| image_size =150px\n| caption =K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol's glyph\n| reign =?-359\n| coronation =\n| full name = \n| predecessor =[[Unen Bahlam]]\n| successor =[[Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I]]\n| spouse  =\n| issue =Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I\n| royal house =\n| father =\n| mother =\n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| death_date =May 23, 359?\n| death_place =\n| date of burial =\n| place of burial =\n| religion     =[[Maya religion]] \n|}}\n'''K\u02bcinich Muwaan Jol''',<ref group=\"N\">The ruler's name, when transcribed is '''K\u02bcINICH-[MUWAN]JOL''', translated \"Radiant Hawk Skull\", Martin & Grube 2008, p.27.</ref> (died 359) was ''[[ajaw]]'' of the [[maya civilization|Maya]] city-state of [[Tikal]]. He was father of Chak Tok Ich\u02bcaak I and he ruled until 359.<ref>Martin & Grube 2008, p.27.</ref><ref group=\"N\">These are the dates indicated on the Maya inscriptions in [[Mesoamerican Long Count calendar]], Death: 8.16.2.6.0 11 Ajaw 13 Pop, Martin & Grube 2008, p.27</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=\"N\"}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|indent=yes}}<!--BEGIN biblio format. If indent param. is used,  Pls use a colon (:) instead of asterisk (*) for bullet markers in the references list -->\n:{{cite book|author=Martin, Simon|authorlink=Simon Martin (Mayanist)|author2=[[Nikolai Grube]]|year=2008|title=Chronicle of the Maya Kings and Queens: Deciphering the Dynasties of the Ancient Maya|location=London and New York|publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]]|edition=2nd|isbn=9780500287262|oclc=191753193}}\n{{refend}}<!-- END biblio format style -->\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{succession box|title=[[