{"title_page": "Dolce & Gabbana", "text_new": "{{redirect2|D & G|Gabbana|the region in Scotland|Dumfries and Galloway|the fashion designer|Stefano Gabbana|the Jamaican beverage company|Desnoes & Geddes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{coord|45.469045|9.2072378|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Dolce & Gabbana S.R.L.\n| logo = [[File:Dolce and Gabbana.svg|225px]]\n| caption = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{Tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| type = [[Societ\u00e0 a Responsabilit\u00e0 Limitata#Italy|Societ\u00e0 a responsabilit\u00e0 limitata]]\n| traded_as = \n| industry = Luxury retail\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1985|df=yes}}<br>[[Milan]], Italy\n| founders = [[Domenico Dolce]]<br> [[Stefano Gabbana]]\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location = Milan\n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Alfonso Dolce, CEO|Cristiana Ruella, COO}}\n| products = Clothing, footwear, handbags, sunglasses, watches, jewellery, perfumes and cosmetics\n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \u20ac1.29 billion (2017/2018)<ref name=\"businessinsider\">{{cite news |last=Scozzari |first=Carlotta |date=5 September 2018 |title=Il 2018 di Dolce & Gabbana: fatturato stabile, utile gi\u00f9 e niente dividendo per i due soci |url=https://it.businessinsider.com/i-conti-di-dolce-gabbana-fatturato-stabile-utile-giu-e-niente-dividendo-per-i-due-soci/ |work=Business Insider Italia |language=Italian}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \u20ac60.5 million<ref name=\"businessinsider\"/>\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 3,150\n| parent = Dolce & Gabbana Luxembourg S.\u00e0.r.l.\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| footnotes = \n| location_country = Italy\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.dolcegabbana.com/}}\n| romanized = \n| former type = \n| intl = \n| bodystyle = \n}}\n'''Dolce & Gabbana''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8dolt\u0283e e \u0261ab\u02c8ba\u02d0na}})<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=d\u00f3lce |url=https://www.dizionario-italiano.it/dizionario-italiano.php?lemma=DOLCE100 |encyclopedia=Dizionario Italiano |language=Italian |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=gabb\u00e0na |url=https://www.dizionario-italiano.it/dizionario-italiano.php?lemma=GABBANA100 |encyclopedia=Dizionario Italiano |language=Italian |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref> is an Italian [[Luxury goods|luxury]] [[fashion house]]<ref name=\"Vernon\">{{cite news | url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/focus/story/0,6903,1418537,00.html | title = Mixing business and pleasure | date = 20 February 2005 | accessdate = 27 July 2007 | last = Vernon | first = Polly | location = London | work = The Guardian }}</ref> founded in 1985 in [[Legnano]] by Italian designers [[Domenico Dolce]] and [[Stefano Gabbana]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/dolce-gabbana_(Dizionario-di-Economia-e-Finanza)/ | work=Dizionario di Economia e Finanza \u2013 Enciclopedia italiana | date= | accessdate=17 November 2014 | title=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n\nThe two met in [[Milan]] in 1980 and designed for the same fashion house. In 1982, they established a designer consulting studio; in time it grew to become \"Dolce & Gabbana\". They presented their first women's collection in 1985<ref name=Givhan2012>{{cite news|last=Givhan|first=Robin|title=Ob-la-di, Ob-la-da, Bras Go On|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/03/18/the-evolution-of-the-bra-from-mad-men-s-day-to-our-own.html|accessdate=15 October 2012|newspaper=Newsweek|date=2 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927215141/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/03/18/the-evolution-of-the-bra-from-mad-men-s-day-to-our-own.html|archive-date=27 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> in Milan, where a year later their store would open its doors.\n\nIn 1988, they launched a leotard line, and in 1989 they began designing underwear and swimming costumes. Dolce & Gabbana started to export their products to Japan and other countries including the United States, where they founded their own showroom in 1990. In 1992, the same year they presented their men's collection, they also launched their first perfume Dolce & Gabbana. They won the [[Woolmark]] award in 1991, and Perfume's Academy \"Most Feminine Flavor of the Year\" in 1993 for their fragrance Dolce & Gabbana Parfum. By the end of the 1990s, the company's revenues were around [[United States dollar|US$]]500&nbsp;million and in 2003 their revenue reached $633&nbsp;million. By 2005, their turnover was [[Euro|\u20ac]]600 million.<ref name=\"Vogue.com UK\">{{cite web | title = Who's Who \u2013 Dolce & Gabbana Biography | work = Vogue UK | url = http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/080421-dolce--gabbana-biography.aspx | accessdate = 27 May 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080907145531/http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/080421-dolce--gabbana-biography.aspx | archivedate = 7 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== The definition gn house ==\n\n=== Early collections ===\nThe first collection from the design duo was shown in October 1985<ref name=\"Givhan2012\"/><ref name=BPRT>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=H5oadQtleT4C&pg=PA206&dq=history+of+dolce+and+gabbana+collections#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20dolce%20and%20gabbana%20collections&f=false |title=The Great Fashion Designers |author=Brenda Polan and Roger Trendre |year=2009 |publisher=Berg |page=206|isbn=9781847882271 }}</ref> alongside five other up-and-coming Italian labels as part of [[Milan Fashion Week]]. The two did not have enough money to hire models or provide accessories for them, so they sought help from their friends. The models (their friends) simply wore their personal items to complement the clothing. They used a bed sheet that Dolce had brought from home as their stage curtain.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/07/16/dolce.gabbana.interview/index.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana: Fashion's golden duo |date=21 July 2012 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |publisher=[[CNN International]] |author=Stefanie Blendis and Gisella Deputato}}</ref>\n\nThe pair labeled their first collection ''Real Women'', due in part to the use of local women as models on the runway.<ref name=BPRT /> Sales from their first collection were disappointing enough for Gabbana to cancel the fabric order they'd put in to create their second collection. However, Dolce's family offered to help meet their costs when the two visited them in [[Sicily]] over Christmas, while incidentally, the fabric company did not receive the cancellation notice in time so the fabric was ready for them back in Milan upon their return.<ref name=TNY>{{cite news |title=Hands and Eyes: When Dolce met Gabbana |author= John Seabrook |publisher=[[The New Yorker]]| date=14 March 2005 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/03/14/050314fa_fact1?currentPage=all}}</ref> They produced the next collection in 1986 and opened their first store that same year.<ref name=BPRT /> [[Michael Gross (writer)|Michael Gross]] wrote of their third collection in a 1992 interview, \"They were a secret known only to a handful of Italian fashion editors. Their few models changed behind a rickety screen. They called their collection of T-shirt-cotton and elastic-silk pieces, Transformation.\" The clothing in this collection came with instructions on the seven different ways a piece could be worn in an outfit, as the wearer could use [[Velcro]] and snaps to alter the clothing's form.<ref name=MGNYM />\n\nTheir fourth collection was the first to make a significant impact on the Italian fashion market. In this collection, Dolce drew upon his Sicilian roots. The collection's advertising campaign was shot by photographer [[Ferdinando Scianna]] in Sicily, and featured Dutch model [[Marpessa Hennink]] in black and white pictures<ref name=italia>{{cite journal|last1=Locatelli|first1=Rossella|title=Marpessa - Vogue Italia Encyclo|journal=Vogue Italia|url=http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/people/m/marpessa|accessdate=7 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411185716/http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/people/m/marpessa|archive-date=11 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=clase>{{cite journal|last1=Mu\u00f1oz Martinez-Mora|first1=Ines|title=Marpessa Clase Superior|journal=Vogue Espa\u00f1a|date=May 2013|pages=206\u2013216|trans-title=Marpessa Top Class|language=Spanish}}</ref> inspired by the Italian cinema of the 1940s. They continued the use of Italian cinema as inspiration in their fifth collection, drawing on the work of filmmaker [[Luchino Visconti]] and his film ''[[The Leopard (1963 film)|The Leopard]]''.<ref name=BPRT />\n\nOne of the pieces from their fourth collection was labeled \"The Sicilian Dress\" by the fashion press, and was named by author Hal Rubenstein as one of the 100 most important dresses ever designed. It is considered to be the most representative piece of this era for the brand. Rubenstein described the piece in 2012 by writing, \"The Sicilian dress is the essence of Dolce & Gabbana, the brand's sartorial touchstone. The dress takes its cue from a slip\u2014but it's a slip that's adorned [[Anna Magnani]], and it's a silhouette that has graced [[Anita Ekberg]], [[Sophia Loren]], [and so forth]. The straps fit tight to the body just as bra straps would; the neckline runs straight across but gets waylaid at least twice, once on each side to caress each breast and in the middle to meet an uplifting tuck that's giving a gentle push up. The slip doesn't just slide down, but comes in at the waist to hold the figure firmly but not too tightly and then widens to emphasise the hips, only to fall with a slight taper at the knees to guarantee that the hips will sway when the wearer walks.\"<ref name=HB>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KvzSrWl5QP0C&pg=PT202&dq=dolce+and+gabbana+collection#v=onepage&q=dolce%20and%20gabbana%20collection&f=false |title=100 Unforgettable Dresses |author=Hal Rubenstein |publisher=Harper Collins |year=2012|isbn=9780062198884 }}</ref>\n\n=== The 1980s and 1990s ===\nIn 1987, the two launched a separate knitwear line and in 1989, they started designing a lingerie line and a beachwear line. Two years later, they launched their leotard line. In 1989, Dolce & Gabbana opened their first store in Japan in partnership with Kashiyama Co. They started to export their products to the United States, where they founded their own showroom in 1990. In 1992, the same year that they presented their men\u2019s collection, they also launched their first perfume Dolce & Gabbana. They won an \u201cOscar des Parfums\u201d for best male perfume in 1996 from the French Parfum Academy, the first time ever that the title has been awarded to an Italian brand. Towards the end of the 1990s their sales were around $500 million and in 2003 alone, their revenue reached $633.2 million.\nIn 1990, they launched their first men's collection.<ref name=VSB /> That year, they also moved the design house into its first official offices and began to design gowns and other more expensive pieces in addition to their original clothing.<ref name=MGNYM /> Their 1990 Spring/Summer women's collection referenced the mythological painting of [[Raphael]], and the duo began to build a reputation for crystal-encrusted clothing. The 1991 Fall/Winter women's collection was also adorned by trinkets, including [[filigree]] medals and embellished [[corset]]s. The 1992 Fall/Winter women's collection was then inspired by the silver screen of the 1950s, though the collection still included crystal embellished body suits.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-archive-embellishments/2011/11/27 |work=Swide Magazine |date=27 November 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=Dolce & Gabbana and their Private Renaissance |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, their men's collection was awarded the Woolmark Award for the most innovative men's collection of the year.<ref name=BIOCH /> What is considered to be their first foray into international recognition came when [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] wore a corset made of gemstones and an accompanying jacket from Dolce & Gabbana at the 1991 [[New York City]] premiere of ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare|Truth or Dare]]: In Bed with Madonna''. The duo then partnered with Madonna in 1993 to design over 1500 costumes for the artist's ''[[Girlie Show]]'' international tour in support of her 1992 album ''[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]''.<ref name=VSB>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=Hemsvn9ZbRkC&pg=PA224&dq=history+of+dolce+and+gabbana+collections#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20dolce%20and%20gabbana%20collections&f=false |pages=223\u2013225 |title=The Berg Companion to Fashion |author=Valerie Steele |publisher=Berg |year=2010 |accessdate=3 May 2012|isbn=9781847885920 }}</ref> In an interview about the costumes, Madonna stated that, \"Their clothes are sexy with a sense of humor\u2014like me.\"<ref name=MGNYM>{{cite news |author=Michael Gross |title=La Dolce (& Gabbana) Vita |work=[[New York Magazine]] |date=7 September 1992 |pages=16\u201317}}</ref> In 1994, the house's trademark [[double-breasted]] jacket was named \"La Turlington\" after model [[Christy Turlington]]. That same year the company launched its second main line\u2014D&G, a line aimed at younger individuals. In 1996 the D&G runway show was streamed only on the Internet and not the runway, in an experimental move towards new media. That year Dolce & Gabbana also designed the costumes for the film ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''.<ref name=VGP />\n\nIn the film industry, both Dolce & Gabbana appeared in the 1995 film ''[[The Star Maker (1995 film)|The Star Maker]] (L'Uomo delle Stelle)'' by director [[Giuseppe Tornatore]], playing minor roles as extras. They appeared in more significant cameo roles in [[Rob Marshall]]'s film-adaptation of ''[[Nine (2009 live-action film)|Nine]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.graziadaily.co.uk/fashion/archive/2009/12/03/dolce---gabbana-turn-film-stars.htm |work=Grazia Daily |date=3 December 2009 |author=Angela Bottolph |accessdate=29 May 2012 |title=Dolce & Gabbana turn film stars!}}</ref> As stylists, they also worked on the music video ''[[All You Need Is Now|Girl Panic!]]'' by [[Duran Duran]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |title=Supermodel Summit |author=Lauren Milligan |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2011/06/13/supermodels-in-duran-duran-video-dolce-and-gabbana |date=13 June 2011 |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of market expansion, in 1989 Dolce & Gabbana signed an agreement with the Kashiyama group to open their first boutique in Japan. They released their first fragrance for women in 1992, called \"Dolce & Gabbana Pour Femme\", which was awarded the Perfume Academy's 1993 award for best feminine fragrance of the year. Their first male fragrance, \"Dolce & Gabbana pour Homme\", was the recipient of the best masculine fragrance of the year award from the same Academy in 1995.<ref name=BIOCH>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/dolce-gabbana.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana |accessdate=29 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815181601/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/dolce-gabbana.html |archivedate=15 August 2012 }}</ref> That year Dolce & Gabbana's collections caused a controversy with the British and Italian press, when they selected the American gangster motif as inspiration for their work.<ref>{{cite book |page=19 |title=Fashion at the Edge: Spectacle, Modernity, and Deathliness |author=Caroline Evans |publisher=Yale University Press |year=2003}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana transposed this Fall/Winter 1995 inspiration onto women's wear, which critics stated brought an erotic edge to the clothing. The duo had used the motif before in 1992 when photographer [[Steven Meisel]] shot an ad campaign for the house in which the models posed in \"gangster chic\". This included wide-lapelled 1930s style coats and black leather caps.<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashion, Desire and Anxiety: Image and Morality in the 20th Century |pages=39\u201340 |author=Rebecca Arnold |year=2001 |publisher=I.B. Tauris}}</ref>\n\nAuthor Nirupama Pundir stated that, \"Dolce & Gabbana, with their superfeminine and fantastical style, broke away from the serious and sober-minded fashions that dominated during much of the Nineties.\"<ref>{{cite book |page=40 |title=Fashion Technology: Today And Tomorrow |author=Nirupama Pundir |publisher=Mittal Publications |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\nDolce & Gabbana continued to work with Madonna, designing the costumes for her [[Drowned World Tour]] in 2001, in support of her 2000 album ''[[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]''.<ref name=VGP>{{cite web |url=http://www.vogue.com/voguepedia/Dolce_%26_Gabbana |title=Dolce & Gabbana |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> They also designed costumes for the international tours of [[Missy Elliott]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], and [[Mary J. Blige]].<ref name=VGP /><ref>{{cite book |page=55 |title= Cherry Bomb: The Ultimate Guide to Becoming a Better Flirt, a Tougher Chick, and a Hotter Girlfriend\u2014and to Living Life Like a Rock Star |publisher=Simon & Schuster |author=Carrie Bornillo-Vrenna |year=2008}}</ref> In 1999, the duo appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in support of singer [[Whitney Houston]], who used the show to debut the Dolce & Gabbana designed costumes for her ''[[My Love Is Your Love]]'' tour, considered by fashion and music critics to be unusually ''risqu\u00e9''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Celebrity-Spotlight/Looking-Back-at-Whitney-Houston/(imageIndex)/14/(play)/false#mode=base;slide=14; |title=Looking Back at Whitney Houston |author=Britt Aboutaleb |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The duo continued to design costumes for musical artists through the 2000s, including the costumes for [[Kylie Minogue]]'s [[Showgirl Homecoming]] tour.<ref name=VGP /> Madonna also participated in Dolce & Gabbana's 2010 advertising campaigns.<ref name=HB />\n\nIn the 2000s, Dolce & Gabbana took a great deal of inspiration from the sport of football as well. In 2003 the men's line took its main inspiration from the world's great football stars.<ref name=VSB /> Other forms of art began taking inspirations from Dolce & Gabbana too. In 2003 dance music artist [[Frankie Knuckles]] said that the fashion house was a \"great barometer\" for trends in both fashion and music.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 November 2003 |work=[[Billboard Magazine]] |author=Michale Paoletta |title=Armani Conjures 'Night' for its Second A/X Disc |page=28}}</ref> As for their impact on the design world, in 2002 the corsets that were a key part of Dolce & Gabbana's early designs were revived by many of Europe's main designers as a trend.<ref>{{cite news |page=74 |work=Out Magazine |title=A model designers |date=March 2002 |author=Brendan Lemon}}</ref> In recent years Dolce & Gabbana has begun holding private viewings of their new collections for buyers, in order to sell their collections before they become public and to pre-empt the copying of their designs by [[Fast fashion|fast fashion companies]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Beating the Commodity Trap: How to Maximize Your Competitive Position and Increase Your Pricing Power |author=Richard A. D'Aveni |publisher=Harvard Business Press |year=2009 |page=34}}</ref>\n\nBy 2005 their turnover was \u20ac597 million.<ref name=\"Vogue.com UK\"/> In 2006, the company started a new journey in accessories and leather goods for men and women. The company also ventured into cosmetics, with Scarlett Johansson as the face of the advertising campaign.\n[[File:Dolce e Gabbana (26441884825).jpg|thumb|Stefano Gabbana (left) and Domenico Dolce (right) in 2016]]\nIn 2012, D&G was merged with Dolce & Gabbana in order to strengthen the main line. The final independent D&G collection was the Spring/Summer 2012 collection shown in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2011/03/03/dolce-and-gabbana-considers-merging-dandg-line |title=The End of D&G |work=[[Vogue UK]] |author=Ella Alexander |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' published in 2005 that, \"Dolce and Gabbana are becoming to the two-thousands what [[Prada]] was to the nineteen-nineties and Armani was to the nineteen-eighties\u2014''gli stilisti'' whose sensibility defines the decade.\"<ref name=TNY /> As for personal awards, in both 1996 and 1997 Dolce & Gabbana were named by ''[[FHM]]'' as the designers of the year. In 2003 ''[[GQ Magazine]]'' named Dolce & Gabbana among their \"Men of the Year\". The following year readers of ''[[Elle (magazine)|British Elle]]'' voted Dolce & Gabbana the best international designers at the 2004 Elle Style Awards.<ref name=AWD>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbana.com/corporate/en/history/international-awards.html |title=International Awards |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana celebrated the 20th anniversary of their brand on 19 June 2010 at the Piazza della la Scala and [[Palazzo Marino]] in Milan. A public exhibition was also held the following day that included a room in which several dozen televisions were piled haphazardly upon each other, each showing a different collection from the design house's twenty-year history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dolce&Gabbana 20th Anniversary. A day in history. A video. |author=Dolce & Gabbana |publisher=Youtube: Dolce & Gabbana Channel |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9k3c0DtbiZw |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Brands ==\n[[File:D&G Golden Sneakers.jpg|thumb|A pair of Dolce & Gabbana's Golden Sneakers.]]\nDolce & Gabbana had two central lines (D&G and Dolce&Gabbana) until 2012, when the lines merged under the label Dolce & Gabbana.\n\n=== Dolce&Gabbana ===\nDolce&Gabbana (spelled without spaces, unlike the name of the company) specialises in luxury items inspired by high-designs and is more formal and 'timeless', responding to long-term trends as well as seasonal changes.<ref name=AAB>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Hemsvn9ZbRkC&pg=PA225&dq=Dolce%26Gabbana++rather+than+seasonal+changes#v=onepage&q=Dolce%26Gabbana%20%20rather%20than%20seasonal%20changes&f=false |title=The Berg Companion to Fashion |author=Valerie Steele |publisher=Berg |page=225 |year=2010|isbn=9781847885920 }}</ref> \nIn February 2010, it was announced that American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] would design a collection of sunglasses titled ''MDG'', set to be released in May of that year.\nIt also offers fragrances for men and women. An example is 'The One' which is a perfume by Dolce&Gabbana.\n\n=== D & G ===\nD & G was the younger, more flamboyant [[diffusion line]] of the brand. Unlike Dolce&Gabbana, D&G sold [[watches]] as well as clothing: watches were manufactured by Naloni and [[Binda Group]]. In 2011, Dolce & Gabbana decided to discontinue the D & G-line in order to put \"more strength and energy\" into their other collections.<ref name=\"NY Mag\">{{cite journal| url=http://NY Mag.com/daily/fashion/2012/06/dolce-gabbana-to-launch-couture-on-july-9.html| title=Dolce & Gabbana to launch Couture| journal=NY Mag| accessdate=29 June 2012}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Other lines ===\nDolce & Gabbana created a [[Wedding dress|bridal]] collection, but only between 1992 and 1998. The Dolce & Gabbana Home Collection\u2014started in 1994\u2014was also discontinued in 1999, with the exception of unique pieces being created for D&G premises. The first women's beachwear collection was developed in 1989, followed by the first men's beachwear collection in 1992. D&G launched an eyewear line in 1998 and a timepieces line in 2000. That same year D&G launched both a men's and women's underwear collection, separate from their Dolce & Gabbana lingerie collection. In 2001 they launched the D&G Junior line for children. In 2006 the duo launched the Anamalier line of leopard print accessories for women, and in 2007 they launched a line of [[crocodile]] travel cases for men. Other bags produced by the house include the Miss Sicily tote bag,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.com/vogue-daily/article/editors-eye-february/ |title=Editors' Eye: The Ten Things We Loved (or Longed For) This February |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |author=Tabitha Simmons |work=[[Vogue UK]]}}</ref> and the \"Dolce\" bag, offered in straw and leather.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.glamour.com/fashion/blogs/slaves-to-fashion/2012/01/it-bag-alert-dolce-gabbanas-do.html |title=Celebrity Obsession Alert: Dolce & Gabbana's \"Dolce\" Bag Is Everything For Spring |date=27 January 2012 |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |author=Tracy Lomrantz}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 they launched their first line of color cosmetics,<ref name=DGGH /> with [[Scarlett Johansson]] as the face of the advertising campaign.<ref name=Scarl /> Dolce & Gabbana launched its first line of fine jewellery in late 2011 with an 80-piece line including bejewelled rosaries, charm bracelets, and necklaces.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/jewellery/news/2011/11/9/dolce-and-gabbana-launch-fine-jewellery |work=[[Vogue UK]] |author=Lisa Niven |date=9 November 2011 |title=Dolce's Jewels |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> They later launched a fine jewellery collection for men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfluxe.net/fit-for-a-king-dolce-gabbanas-fine-jewelry/|title=\u00bb Fit For a King: Dolce & Gabbana's Fine Jewellery Collection|last=Matthews|first=Damion|date=12 November 2015|website=SFLUXE|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana have received several awards for their fragrances, as was described in the above sections. Their current fragrances include: \"The One\", \"Sport\", \"[[Light Blue (fragrance)|Light Blue]]\", \"Dolce\", \"Classic\", \"Sicily\", \"The One Rose\", and the original scents \"Pour Homme\" and \"Parfum\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/dg/perfumes/ |title=Perfumes |accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref> On 16 October 2014, the company announced that [[Colin Farrell]] would be the face of their new fragrance called \"Intenso.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/2014/10/16/colin-farrell-face-of-dolce-and-gabbana-campaign|title=Colin Farrell, Face Of Dolce & Gabbana Campaign (Vogue.co.uk)|work=Vogue UK}}</ref>\n\n=== Internet ===\nDolce & Gabbana made the \"DG\" logo an iconic and instantly recognizable symbol,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.famouslogos.net/dolce-gabbana-logo/ | title = Dolce & Gabbana Logo&nbsp;\u2013 Design and History | work = FamousLogos.net | accessdate =7 May 2011}}</ref> but they were never able to get the matching internet address DG.com.\nIn fact, DG.com is one of the oldest Internet domains and was already registered in 1986 by the computer company [[Data General]], now defunct. After that company closed in 1999, the url went to [[EMC Corporation|EMC]] before [[Dollar General]] purchased it in 2010 after a bidding war with Dolce & Gabbana.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wayback Machine: 2/3/11 |url=http://www.dollargeneral.com/ |accessdate=19 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107040228/http://www.dollargeneral.com// |archivedate=7 January 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Partnerships ==\n\n=== Sports ===\nDolce & Gabbana has designed the on-field attire for [[A.C. Milan]] since 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/sport-story-2004/2010/10/2 |title=2004: a soccer obsession is born |date=2 October 2010 |work=Swide Magazine |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In addition to having their on-field uniforms designed by Dolce & Gabbana, A.C. Milan players also dress in team-issued Dolce & Gabbana attire when at official functions off the field.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/grant_wahl/07/28/oguchi.onyewu/ |title=Onyewu finding his way into Milan |author=Grant Wahl |date=28 July 2009 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> The duo also designed the off-field suits for the [[Italy national football team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/designers/d/dolcegabbana |title=Dolce&Gabbana |author=Sara Pizzi |work=[[Vogue Italia]] |accessdate=29 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113015248/http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/designers/d/dolcegabbana |archive-date=13 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2010, Dolce & Gabbana signed a three-year deal with the [[Chelsea F.C.]] to design and provide the club's on- and off-field uniforms and attire. The deal included the creation of clothing for female staff members in addition to male staff members and the players themselves. The off-field outfits designed for the club included a dark blue suit featuring the lion symbol on the breast pocket. The designers also re-designed the club's director's lounge and main office reception area.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG7913107/Dolce-and-Gabbana-and-Chelsea-Football-Club.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana and Chelsea Football Club |date=27 July 2012 |author=Hilary Alexander |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820012529/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG7913107/Dolce-and-Gabbana-and-Chelsea-Football-Club.html |archivedate=20 August 2012 }}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana were also the named sponsors of the Milano Thunder Italian Boxing Team.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldseriesboxing.com/teams/milan/information.aspx |accessdate= 29 May 2012 |title= Dolce&Gabbana Milano Thunder Italian Boxing Team |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120629182234/http://www.worldseriesboxing.com/teams/milan/information.aspx |archivedate= 29 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Products ===\nIn 2006, Dolce & Gabbana partnered with [[Motorola]] to produce the [[Motorola RAZR|Motorola V3i Dolce & Gabbana cellular phone]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/CNet/story?id=2612660#.T8Ua3txYtD0 |date=12 December 2006 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |title=Motorola V3i Dolce & Gabbana |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In 2009, Dolce & Gabbana partnered with [[Sony Mobile Communications|Sony Ericsson]] to produce a version of its Jalou [[Mobile phone|cellular phone]] line with [[Gold#Jewelry|24-karat gold details]] and the logo of the design house emblazoned on the co-designed piece of technology.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://gazetaweb.globo.com/noticia.php?c=7887&e=11 |date=27 October 2009 |work=Gazeta de Algoas |title= Celular Jalou 'veste' Dolce & Gabbana |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana also partnered with [[Citro\u00ebn]] to co-design a version of their [[Citro\u00ebn C3|C3 Pluriel vehicle]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.chronica.it/2008/02/27/auto-griffate-non-solo-una-moda-ma-uno-stile-di-vita/ |date=27 February 2008 |title=Auto griffate: non solo una moda, ma uno stile di vita |author=Eleonora Marini |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=Chronica}}</ref> In 2010 Dolce & Gabbana partnered with [[Martini (vermouth)|Martini]] to produce a \"gold edition\" of its vermouth.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.moetodete.bg/zvezdni-novini/martini-gold-by-dolce-and-gabbana-noviyat-svetski-hit.html |title=Martini Gold by Dolce & Gabbana |publisher=Moetodete.bg |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In 2010 the design house then teamed with singer Madonna to release a co-designed line of sunglasses called MDG.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2010/03/16/us-fashion-madonna-dolcegabbana-idUKTRE62F3RK20100316 |title=Madonna designs Dolce & Gabbana sunglasses |author=Marie-Louise Gumuchian |date=16 March 2010 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n== Advertising campaigns ==\nThe commercial for the first women fragrance of Dolce & Gabbana ran for several years in Italy, created by filmmaker [[Giuseppe Tornatore]], scored by [[Ennio Morricone]], and starred actress [[Monica Bellucci]]. The 30-second commercial begins with a man slapping an octopus against the stone ridges of a [[tide pool]]. He stands and looks around his surroundings at different women going about their daily lives. One woman (Bellucci) is seen changing into a 1950s-style bathing suit behind a white sheet being held up by two other women. After she changes, she tosses her bra atop a [[Opuntia|prickly pear cactus]] and walks towards the ocean. Later she is seen lying atop a well-made bed, and the man who saw her is standing outside her window, holding her bra up to his nose. The film closes with the image of the Dolce & Gabbana fragrance bottles against a black backdrop.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-video-archive-perfume/2011/10/9 |work=Swide Magazine |date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=1994: Monica Bellucci and Giuseppe Tornatore for Dolce & Gabbana |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref> In 2003, the Dolce & Gabbana perfume Sicily was advertised in another commercial about a Sicilian funeral, which was also directed by Giuseppe Tornatore.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-archive-funerale/2011/10/30 |work=Swide Magazine |date=30 October 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=Funeral alla Dolce & Gabbana |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref>\n\n[[Gisele B\u00fcndchen]] starred in the 2006 commercial for the fragrance \"The One\", featuring Bundchen in front of a vanity mirror being made up, with flashes of a mob of cameramen interspersed; she then puts on a golden dress, shoes, and a pair of D&G sunglasses.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-video-archive-the-one/2011/11/13 |work=Swide Magazine |date=13 November 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=Gisele is The One |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref> Photographers and filmmakers that have worked with Dolce & Gabbana on advertising campaigns have included Giampaolo Barbieri,<ref>{{cite news |title=Photo Spread |work=GQ Russia |date=March 2011 |pages=242\u2013245}}</ref> Michel Comte,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michelcomte.org/index.php/the-artist.html |title=The Artist |accessdate=19 May 2012 |year=2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215192118/http://www.michelcomte.org/index.php/the-artist.html |archivedate=15 February 2010 }}</ref> Fabrizio Ferri,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/Spring-summer-1987----the-power-of-a-DolceGabbana-transformation/2010/6/13 |title=Spring/Summer 1987: The Power of Dolce & Gabbana Transformation |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> [[Steven Klein (photographer)|Steven Klein]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/2009/12/dolce-gabbana-madonna-by-steven-klein-for-dolce-gabbana-ss-2010.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana: Madonna by Steven Klein for Dolce & Gabbana S/S 2010 |work=OhLaLa Magazine |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115050936/http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/2009/12/dolce-gabbana-madonna-by-steven-klein-for-dolce-gabbana-ss-2010.html |archive-date=15 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2007/02/dolce_gabbana#slide=1 |title=Stefano and Domenico's Dolce Vita |work=W Magazine |date=February 2007 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207012423/http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2007/02/dolce_gabbana#slide=1 |archivedate=7 December 2014 }}</ref> [[Steven Meisel]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.designscene.net/2008/06/dolce-gabbana-fall-winter-2006.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana Fall Winter 2006: The Renaissance by Steven Meisel |work=Design Scene |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Mert + Marcus,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/Life/Bellezza/felicity-jones-make-up/2012/2/13 |title=Felicity Jones by Mert+Marcus for Dolce &Gabbana Make-up |work=Swide Magazine |date=13 February 2012}}</ref> [[Jean Baptiste Mondino]],<ref name=Scarl>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch_scarlett_johansson_likes_her_lips_for_kissing_in_dolce_gabbana_ad_by_ |title=Watch: Scarlett Johansson Likes Her Lips For Kissing In Dolce & Gabbana Ad By Jean-Baptiste Mondino |date=24 October 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |author=Kevin Jagernauth |publisher=Indiewire |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227181743/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch_scarlett_johansson_likes_her_lips_for_kissing_in_dolce_gabbana_ad_by_ |archive-date=27 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ferdinando Scianna,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.magnumphotos.com/Catalogue/Ferdinando-Scianna/1987/Dutch-model-MARPESSA-photographed-for-DOLCE-_-GABBANA-1987-NN145557.html |title= Ferdinando Scianna \u2013 Dutch model, MARPESSA, photographed for DOLCE & GABBANA. 1987. |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Giampaolo Sgura,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/giampaolo-sgura/ |work= Ohlala Magazine |title= Alfred Kovac & Valerija Sestic For D&G Summer 2012 Eyewear |accessdate= 19 May 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141204171742/http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/giampaolo-sgura/ |archivedate= 4 December 2014 }}</ref> [[Mario Sorrenti]],<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2008/03/mario_sorrenti#slide=1 |title=On Fire |date=March 2008 |work=W Magazine |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> S\u00f8lve Sundsb\u00f8,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9405E2D6173DF930A1575BC0A96F9C8B63 |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Pulse; Wearing the Works |author=Karin Nelson |date=23 August 2009 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> [[Mario Testino]],<ref>{{cite news |url= http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/columns/phong-luu/TMG9082454/Meet-Adam-Senn-the-new-face-of-Dolce-and-Gabbanas-The-One-Sport.html |title= Meet Adam Senn, the new face of Dolce & Gabbana's The One Sport |date=15 February 2012 |author=Phong Luu |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Giuseppe Tornatore, and [[Mariano Vivanco]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.papermag.com/2012/05/why_is_this_dolce_gabanna_post.php |title= Why Is This Dolce & Gabbana Poster Worth $500? |author=Gary Pini |date=7 May 2012 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana have won two Leadawards for their campaigns from Germany's leading advertising awards. In 2004 they won for their Fall/Winter 2003/04 campaign<ref>{{cite web |url= http://leadacademy.de/2004/preistraeger.html |title=The Winners |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> and in 2006 they won for their Fall/Winter 2005/06 campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://leadacademy.de/2006/preistraeger.html |title=The Winners |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Inspirations and style ==\n[[File:Dolce & Gabbana Shop (Via della Spiga - Milan) 02.jpg|thumb|The Dolce & Gabbana store of [[Via della Spiga]] in [[Milan]]]]\nOriginally inspired by eclectic, [[thrift shop]] [[bohemian]] style, Dolce & Gabbana's deeply colored, [[animal print]]s have been described as \"haute hippy dom\" taking inspiration in particular from Italy's prestigious film history. \"When we design it's like a movie (Domenico),\" says Domenico Dolce. \"We think of a story and we design the clothes to go with it (Domenico).\" They claim to be more concerned about creating the best, most flattering clothes than sparking trends, once admitting that they wouldn't mind if their only contribution to fashion history was a black bra (Dolce & Gabbana 2007). [[Sicily]] and [[Sicilian culture]] is the most important style and identity of Dolce & Gabbana.\n\nD & G trademarks include [[underwear-as-outerwear]] (such as corsets and bra fastenings), gangster boss [[pinstripe]] suits, and extravagantly printed coats. Meanwhile, their feminine collections are always backed by powerful ad campaigns, like the black-and-white ads featuring model Marpessa photographed by Ferdinando Scianna in 1987 (Dolce & Gabbana). \"They find their way out of any black dress, any buttoned-up blouse (Domenico),\" says Rossellini. \"The first piece of theirs I wore was a white shirt, very chaste, but cut to make my breasts look as if they were bursting out of it (Domenico).\"\n\nOnce dubbed the \"Gilbert and George of Italian fashion\",<ref name=AAA>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/spy/biographies/dolce-and-gabbana-biography |title=Dolce & Gabbana |author=Jo Craven |date=11 May 2011 |work=Vogue UK |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana gave their fashion interests a musical turn in 1996, by recording their own single, in which they intoned the words \"D&G is love\" over a techno beat (Dolce & Gabbana 2011). Newer to the design game than other heavyweight Italian fashion houses such as [[Armani]] and [[Versace]], the pair acknowledge that luck has played its part in their phenomenal success. By 1997, their company reported a turnover of \u20ac400 million, prompting both designers to announce that they planned to retire by the age of 40 \u2013 a promise they did not keep (Domenico).\n\nAfter the designers spotted a Veneziano painting of Christ on the cross wearing a pair of their branded underwear briefs in the Venice Biennale, they commissioned the artist to do a portrait of them with the Madonna portrayed as the likeness of the chanteuse and performer [[Madonna Ciccone]] and the courtiers as two putti at her feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/758548c8-5d54-11e1-889d-00144feabdc0.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.10magazine.com/article/15176531624/dolce-gabbana-art-house|title=10 Magazine|work=10magazine.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, the company launched a high-end fashion range aimed at wealthy Muslim women featuring a collection of hijabs and abayas printed with daisies, lemons and roses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/07/dolce-gabbana-debuts-luxury-hijab-collection|title=Dolce & Gabbana launches luxury hijab collection|last=Gani|first=Aisha|date=7 January 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\nIn addition to designing clothing, Dolce & Gabbana have co-authored nearly two dozen books featuring photographic narratives as well as collections of their own work. The proceeds of many of these books go to charities including the Children\u2019s Action Network and the Butterfly Onlus \"\u00e9cole sans fronti\u00e8res\" Foundation.<ref name=DGGH /> The following is a bibliography of their literary works:\n\n* ''10 Anni Dolce & Gabbana'' (A collection of the most important advertising and editorial images of the design house's first decade)<ref>{{cite book |title=10 Anni Dolce & Gabbana |year=1996 |publisher=Leonardo Arte SRL |author=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Wildness''<ref>{{cite book |title=Dolce & Gabbana Wildness |year=1997 |publisher=Leonardo Arte SRL |author=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Animal''<ref>{{cite book |title=Animal |author=Dolce & Gabbana |year=1998 |publisher=Abbeville Press}}</ref>\n* ''Hollywood'' (Features over 100 photographs of the movie stars from the post-1985 era)<ref>{{cite book |title=Hollywood |year=2003 |publisher=Assouline |author=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Calcio'' (Photographs of 44 soccer players, 3 teams, and 2 coaches)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marianovivanco.com/biography/ |title=Mariano Vivanco |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514225930/http://www.marianovivanco.com/biography/ |archivedate=14 May 2012 }}</ref>\n* ''A.C. Milan''<ref>{{cite book |title=AC Milan Dressed by Dolce & Gabbana |author=Dolce & Gabbana and Mariano Vivanco |year=2004 |publisher=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Music'' (Features over 150 of globally recognised musicians)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbana.it/books/ |title=Books |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''20 Years Dolce & Gabbana'' (A chronological photographic history of each of the house's collections, using over 1000 photos)<ref name=DGGH>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/corporate/en/history/main-stages.html |title=Group History |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Milan''<ref>{{cite book |title=Milan |author=Dolce & Gabbana and Mariano Vivanco |publisher=Mondadori Electa |year=2006}}</ref>\n* ''2006 Italia'' (A book celebrating the 2006 World Cup title won by Italy)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/books/nazionale/ |accessdate=30 May 2012 |title=2006 Italia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721140640/http://www.dolcegabbana.com/books/nazionale/ |archivedate=21 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* ''Fashion Album'' (Contains over 400 images paying homage to the great fashion photographers of Dolce & Gabbana collections)<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashion Album |author=Dolce & Gabbana and Mariuccia Casadio |publisher=Skira |year=2006}}</ref>\n* ''Secret Ceremony''<ref>{{cite book |title=Secret Ceremony |author=Steven Klein and Dolce & Gabbana |year=2007 |publisher=Dolce & Gabbana SRL}}</ref>\n* ''Family'' (A book that focuses on the family as the center of a man's life)<ref name=DGGH />\n* ''The Good Shepherd'' (A book that illustrates the day of a common shephard, wearing Dolce & Gabbana clothing)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Good Shepherd |author=Michael Roberts |year=2007 |publisher=Dolce & Gabbana SRL}}</ref>\n* ''Milano Beach Soccer''<ref name=DGGH />\n* ''Diamonds & Pearls''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.luxist.com/2008/12/26/dolce-and-gabbanas-i-diamonds-and-pearls-i/ |title=Dolce & Gabbana's Diamonds & Pearls |date=26 December 2008 |publisher=The Luxist |author=Jared Paul Stern |accessdate=30 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223170044/http://www.luxist.com/2008/12/26/dolce-and-gabbanas-i-diamonds-and-pearls-i/ |archivedate=23 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''20 Years of Dolce & Gabbana for Men''<ref>{{cite book |title=20 Years of Dolce & Gabbana for Men |year=2010 |publisher=Mondadori Electa}}</ref>\n* ''Icons 1990\u20132010''<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.2dmblogazine.it/2011/06/icons-dolce-gabbana-1990-2010/ |title=Icons: Dolce & Gabbana 1990\u20132010 |date=1 June 2011 |publisher=2DM |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Fashion Shows 1990 \u2013 2010''<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashion Shows 1990 \u2013 2010 Dolce & Gabbana |publisher=Mondadori Electa |year=2011}}</ref>\n* ''Nazionale Italiana: South Africa 2010'' (A series of images starring the Italian National Football Team during the training sessions preceding the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]])<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/features_fashion/2010/05/world-cup-in-south-africa-puts-soccer-and-fashion-on-the-same-team.html |title=\"Sporno\" Soccer studs pitch Fashion or Futball? |author=Rod Hagwood |date=27 May 2010 |work=[[Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel]] |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530230124/http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/features_fashion/2010/05/world-cup-in-south-africa-puts-soccer-and-fashion-on-the-same-team.html |archivedate=30 May 2012 }}</ref>\n* ''Uomini''<ref>{{cite book |title=Uomini |year=2011 |publisher=Rizzoli |author=Mariano Vivanco and Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2011/01/06/dolce-and-gabbana-coffee-table-book-uomini |work=[[Vogue UK]] |author=Lauren Milligan |title=Dolce Undressed |date=6 January 2011}}</ref>\n* ''Milan Fashion Soccer Players Portraits''<ref>{{cite news |url= http://daman.co.id/dolce-gabbana-celebrates-ac-milan/ |title= Dolce & Gabbana celebrates AC MILAN |date=24 August 2011 |work=DA Man |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''David Gandy'' (A 280-page photographic coffee table book of images chronicling collaborations with British model [[David Gandy]] from 2006 to 2011)<ref>{{cite book |title=David Gandy |author=Dolce & Gabbana |year=2011 |publisher=Rizzoli}}</ref>\n* ''Campioni''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.it/dg/books/campioni/ |title=''Campioni'' |accessdate=3 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Spaces and exhibitions ==\nDolce & Gabbana opened the ''La sede di via San Damiano'' [[atelier]] in September 1995. They opened a combined seven-floor boutique and corporate space ''Lo showroom di via Goldoni'' in 2002, moving from its prior main showroom at Piazza Umanitaria. In July 2006 Dolce & Gabbana then opened a 5,000 square foot show floor ''Lo showroom di via Broggi'' in Milan. The design house also bought the ''Il Metropol'' theatre in Milan, a historic cinema built in the 1940s. It was renovated and reopened in September 2005.<ref name=DGGH /> In 2006 Dolce & Gabbana opened IL GOLD, an establishment with caf\u00e9, bar, bistro, and restaurant areas. This is followed by the opening of a co-sponsored drinking establishment the duo founded at their Milanese men's showroom called the [[Martini (vermouth)|Martini Bar]] in 2003.<ref name=VGP /> An additional Martini Bar was later opened at their Shanghai showroom in 2006.<ref name=DGGH /> In 2009 Dolce & Gabbana had 93 boutiques and 11 factory outlets, and was sold in over 80 countries.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=FEh-FZbsHRoC&pg=PT284&dq=dolce+and+Gabbana+number+of+stores#v=onepage&q=dolce%20and%20Gabbana%20number%20of%20stores&f=false |title= Plunkett's Retail Industry Almanac 2009: Retail Industry Market Research, Statistics, Trends and Leading Companies |author=Jack W. Plunkett |publisher=Plunkett Research |year=2008|isbn= 9781593921392 }}</ref> In all they have 251 mono-brand stores.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/corporate/en/group/profile.html |accessdate=29 May 2012 |title=Group Profile}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States standalone boutiques can be found in [[Bal Harbour]], [[Beverly Hills]], Chicago, [[Houston]], [[Las Vegas]], and New York City. Dolce & Gabbana also operates boutiques in other cities in select department stores: [[Nordstrom]], [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[Neiman Marcus]], and [[Bergdorf Goodman]].\n\nIn addition to developing runway shows and advertising campaigns for its collections, Dolce & Gabbana use their spaces to host photography and other [[art exhibition]]s. Soon after the opening of the Il Metropol, they hosted two exhibitions by artist [[Ron Arad (industrial designer)|Ron Arad]] in the lobby space: ''Blo-Glo'' between April 2006 and April 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/en/events/bloglo_by_ron_arad |title=Blo-Glo by Ron Arad |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> and ''Bodyguards'' in late April 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/en/events/ |title=Bodyguards by Ron Arad |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> They held photography exhibitions featuring the work of [[Enzo Sellerio]] in 2007<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/it/events/fermo_immagine_fotografie_di_enzo_sellerio |title=Freeze: Photos by Enzo Sellerio |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> and [[Herbert List]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/en/events/herbert_list_lo_sguardo_sulla_bellezza_an_eye_for_beauty_ |title=Herbert List: An Eye for Beauty |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> In 2011 Dolce & Gabbana held an open house and architectural exhibition with Studio Piuarch showcasing the studio's various architectural designs and projects since 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2011/04/haute-event-dolce-gabbana-and-studio-piuarch-present-open-house-piuarchdolcegabbana/ |work=Haute Living |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title= Haute Event: Dolce & Gabbana and Studio Piuarch Present Open House \u2013 Piuarch@Dolce&Gabbana |author=Pauline Sung |date=11 April 2011}}</ref> Studio Piuarch built the Dolce & Gabbana headquarters in 2006, which was where the exhibition and open house was held.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.archdaily.com/2458/dolce-gabbana-headquarters-studio-piuarch/ |author=Nico Saieh |title=Dolce & Gabbana Headquarters / Studio Piuarch |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |work=ArchDaily}}</ref>\n\nDolce & Gabbana also uses its spaces for book launches and photographic exhibitions of its own clothing, such as the book launch of their book ''David Gandy'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.style.it/moda/photogallery/protagonisti-ed-eventi/2011/06/20/dolcegabbana-e-david-gandy.aspx |title=Dolce & Gabbana Celebrates with David Gandy |date=20 June 2011 |author=Carolina Rimondi |work=Style.it |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824052603/http://www.style.it/moda/photogallery/protagonisti-ed-eventi/2011/06/20/dolcegabbana-e-david-gandy.aspx |archivedate=24 August 2011 }}</ref> They also use other spaces as well, such as the [[Palazzo della Ragione, Milan|Palazzo della Ragione in Milan]], where in May 2009 they staged a photographic exhibition of over 100 images selected from the history of [[Vogue (magazine)|US Vogue]] over its 90-year history. The exhibition was called ''Extreme Beauty in Vogue''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbana.com/extreme-beauty-in-vogue/ |title= Extreme Beauty in Vogue |accessdate= 19 May 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120516185919/http://www.dolcegabbana.com/extreme-beauty-in-vogue/ |archivedate= 16 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.style.com/peopleparties/parties/scoop/fashionweek-030209_Dolce_Gabbana_Extreme_Beauty/ |title=To the Extreme |accessdate=19 May 2012 |year=2009 |author=Tim Blanks |work=Style.com}}</ref>\n\nThe company has production factories in [[Legnano]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.modemonline.com/fashion/mini-web-sites/fashion-brands/references/maurogasperi |title=Mauro Gasperi |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> and [[Incisa in Val d'Arno]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ymag.it/schede.asp?id=9270 |title= what's up in viapiranesi |date= 14 April 2011 |accessdate= 19 May 2012 |work= Ymag |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111204044424/http://www.ymag.it/schede.asp?id=9270 |archivedate= 4 December 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nDolce & Gabbana has been involved in many controversial cases, with accusations mainly related with [[racism]], [[sexism]] and [[homophobia]].<ref>[https://www.out.com/popnography/2018/11/21/brief-history-dolce-gabbana-being-racist-sexist-and-homophobic A Brief History of Dolce & Gabbana Being Racist, Sexist and Homophobic]</ref><ref>[https://www.dircksey.com.au/2017/07/dolce-and-gabbanah-the-casual-acceptance-of-racism-sexism-hate-speech-and-more-in-the-name-of-fashion/ Dolce and GabbaNAH: The casual acceptance of racism, sexism, hate speech and more in the name of \u2018fashion\u2019]</ref>\n=== Advertising ===\n[[File:1 dolce gabbana.jpg|thumb|2007 D&G advertising image subject to controversy.]]\n\nDolce & Gabbana was publicly criticised by Britain's advertising watchdog [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority (ASA)]] in January 2007, for an advertising campaign showing models brandishing knives.\n\nFollowing complaints from consumer groups in February 2007, Dolce & Gabbana pulled an advertisement in Spain that showed a man holding a woman to the ground by her wrists while a group of men look on. Spain's Labour and Social Affairs Ministry branded the campaign as illegal and humiliating to women, saying the woman's body position had no relation to the products Dolce & Gabbana was trying to sell.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eitb24.com/new/en/B24_36294/life/MILAN-BASED-FASHION-HOUSE-Dolce-Gabbana-angry-at/ | title = Dolce & Gabbana angry at advertising campaign controversy in Spain | work = Euskal Irrati Telebista | date = 23 February 2007 | accessdate =24 February 2007}}</ref> Italian publications followed suit, banning the ad. This advertisement was called \"a glorification of [[gang rape]]\" and declared \"one of the most controversial advertisements in fashion history\" by ''[[Debonair Magazine (U.S.)|Debonair Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Most Controversial Ads in Fashion History|url=http://www.debonairmag.com/the-most-controversial-ads-in-fashion-history/7|accessdate=24 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123220310/http://www.debonairmag.com/the-most-controversial-ads-in-fashion-history/7|archive-date=23 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> When asked about the ad being banned in Spain, Dolce & Gabbana responded that the \"Spaniards were a bit backward.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://nextshark.com/people-are-pissed-at-dolce-gabbana-again-for-these-ads-depicting-gang-rape/|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150321012450/http://nextshark.com/people-are-pissed-at-dolce-gabbana-again-for-these-ads-depicting-gang-rape/|url-status = dead|archivedate = 21 March 2015|title = People Are Pissed at Dolce & Gabbana Again For These Ads Depicting Gang Rape|date = 18 March 2015|accessdate = 14 October 2015|website = NextShark|last = Chan|first = Augustine Reyes}}</ref> According to the Daily Mail, Dolce & Gabbana's ad was said to \"offend the dignity of the woman.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThis particular ad was brought up again seven years later by Kelly Cutrone, a well-known fashion publicist, when she mentioned it on her Twitter account. According to Nextshark.com, \"she slammed Dolce & Gabbana, claiming the ad, which depicts a woman being pinned to the group by a half-naked man as three men look on, simulates a 'gang bang'.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> According to ''The Huffington Post UK'', feminist writer Louise Pennington recently also commented on the image. She stated that, \"This particular image is a representative of an increasingly misogynistic contraction of women in the fashion industry demonstrating very clear links between the fashion-beauty industry and the mainstreaming of pornography. Those who suggest this image is harmless fail to recognize the reality of rape culture and the dehumanization of women's bodies in our pornographic mainstream media.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/03/18/dolce-and-gabbana0gang-rape-advert_n_6893044.html|title = 'Gang Rape' Dolce & Gabbana Advert Brings Yet More Controversy For Brand After 'Synthetic' IVF Comments|date = 18 March 2015|accessdate = 16 November 2015|website = The Huffington Post UK|last = Moss|first = Rachel}}</ref>\n\n=== Hong Kong photo ban ===\n[[File:D&G Hong Kong Racism.jpg|thumb|One of the four streets blocked during the Sunday protest.]]\n\nOn 5 January 2012, ''[[Apple Daily]]'' reported that only Hong Kong residents (and not mainland Chinese or foreigners) had been prevented from taking pictures of Dolce & Gabbana window displays in both their Hong Kong stores, stirring [[Hong Kong-Mainland conflict|anti-Mainland Chinese sentiment]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/template/apple/art_main.php?iss_id=20120105&sec_id=4104&art_id=15954668&av_id=15955030 | title=\u64c5\u7981\u9014\u4eba\u62cd\u7167\u3000\u73b7\u6c61\u8cfc\u7269\u5929\u5802 \u540d\u5e97\u60e1\u9738 D&G |language=Chinese |trans-title= D&G the Tyrannical Luxury Shop Unpermittedly Forbids By-passers to Take Photos, \"Shoppers' Paradise\" Ashamed |work=Apple Daily |location=Hong Kong | date=5 January 2012 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | author=\u6881\u5fa1\u548c\u3001\u76e7\u52c1\u696d\u3001\u4f0d\u96c5\u8b19}}</ref> In particular staff and security personnel at their flagship store on [[Canton Road]] asserted the pavement area outside was private property where photography was forbidden. The actions sparked protests spanning several days and gained international news coverage on 8 January.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/business/protest-at-dolce-and-gabbana-store-in-hong-kong-follows-alleged-ban-on-photography/story-e6frfm1i-1226239375370#ixzz1irefM2CG | title=Protest at Dolce and Gabbana store in Hong Kong follows alleged ban on photography | work=[[News Limited]] Australia|date= 8 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_753234.html | title=Hundreds protest D&G photo 'ban' in Hong Kong |work=The Sunday Times |location=UK|date= 8 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/hongkong/9001001/One-thousand-protest-Dolce-and-Gabbana-Hong-Kong-store-over-photo-ban.html | title=One thousand protest Dolce & Gabbana Hong Kong store over photo ban |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date= 9 January 2012|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/scene/2012/01/09/dolce-gabbana-photo-ban-sparks-protest/ | title=Dolce & Gabbana Photo Ban Sparks Protest|work=The Wall Street Journal|date= 9 January 2012|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Citing the case of Zhou Jiugeng, a Nanjing official whose high-living lifestyle was identified by mainland Chinese internet users using photographs, local news reports speculated that the Dolce & Gabbana photo ban may have been imposed at the request of some wealthy Chinese government officials attempting to block details on the source of their wealth.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20120108/00176_006.html | title=D&G\u4e8b\u4ef6\u8d77\u56e0 \u50b3\u5167\u5730\u9ad8\u5e79\u6295\u8a34 \u6015\u88ab\u626f\u4e0a\u8caa\u6c61|trans-title= Alleged Cause of D&G Incident: Fear of Corruption <nowiki>[</nowiki>Accusations<nowiki>]</nowiki>, Mainland Officials Complain| work=Oriental Daily|date= 8 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/4026624/Chinese-internet-vigilantes-bring-down-another-official.html|title=Chinese internet vigilantes bring down another official|author=Malcolm Moore in Shanghai|date=30 December 2008|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nDolce & Gabbana finally issued a formal apology to the people of Hong Kong from its Milan headquarters on 18 January 2012.<ref>[http://www.am730.com.hk/article.php?article=89703&d=1670 D&G\u51cc\u6668\u300c\u9053\u6b49\u300d \u7db2\u6c11\u62d2\u6536\u300c\u884c\u8ca8\u300d]\uff0cAM730\uff0c19 January 2012</ref><ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2012/01/19/dolce-gabbana-apologizes-for-photo-spat/ Dolce & Gabbana Apologizes for Photo Spat], Wall Street Journal, 19 January 2012</ref>\n\n=== Gay adoption and in vitro fertilization ===\nIn an interview in 16 March 2015 issue of Italian magazine [[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]], Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce caused controversy when they remarked, \"We oppose gay adoptions. The only family is the traditional one.\" They also criticized [[in vitro fertilisation]] (IVF) and [[surrogacy]] by saying, \"No chemical offspring and rented uterus: life has a natural flow, there are things that should not be changed.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.panorama.it/news/cronaca/dolce-gabbana-lunica-famiglia-quella-tradizionale/ | publisher=Panorama | title=Figli e famiglia, la verit\u00e0 di Dolce e Gabbana | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> Since the comments were made by two gay men in an industry often seen as gay-friendly, reactions were especially harsh.\n\nCritics took to social media to voice their opposition, with the hashtag #BoycottDolceGabbana garnering 30,000 tweets on Twitter in five days. Celebrities, including Elton John, Madonna, Victoria Beckham, Ricky Martin, Martina Navratilova and Courtney Love, were among those expressing anger over the remarks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/15/elton-john-boycott-dolce-gabbana-synthetic-ivf-babies-comment|title=Elton John: boycott Dolce & Gabbana over 'synthetic' IVF babies comment|last=Association|first=Press|date=2015-03-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Love said she would \"burn all of her Dolce and Gabbana clothing\", while John, father of two children conceived through IVF, commented, \"How dare you refer to my beautiful children as 'synthetic'. And shame on you for wagging your judgmental little fingers at IVF \u2013 a miracle that has allowed legions of loving people, both straight and gay, to fulfil their dream of having children.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-31907007 | newspaper=BBC | title=Dolce and Gabbana say 'Boycott Elton John' | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> In an Instagram post Madonna, who appeared in a 2010 Dolce & Gabbana campaign, said, \"All babies contain a soul however they come to this earth and their families. There is nothing synthetic about a soul!! So how can we dismiss IVF and surrogacy? Every soul comes to us to teach us a lesson. God has his hand in everything even technology! We are arrogant to think Man does anything on his own. As above so below! Think before you speak.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/19/madonna-dolce-gabbana_n_6901330.html | newspaper=Huffington Post | title=Madonna Responds To The Dolce & Gabbana Controversy | first=Cavan |last=Sieczkowski | date=19 March 2015 | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nMore than 10,000 people signed an online petition calling for Macy's and Debenhams to stop stocking the brand in their department stores, until D&G retracted their statements and apologized. Protesters also gathered outside Dolce & Gabbana\u2019s flagship London shop calling for an international boycott of the luxury fashion store.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2015/mar/19/dolce-gabbana-london-protests-boycott-shop | newspaper=The Guardian | title=Dolce & Gabbana protesters demand boycott outside London shop | first=Aisha | last=Gani | date=19 March 2015 | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nDolce & Gabbana criticized calls for a boycott on their brand as \"medieval\" and called for fans to use the hashtag #BoycottEltonJohn, though it resulted in only 1,500 tweets.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-31907007 |newspaper=BBC News| title=Dolce and Gabbana say 'Boycott Elton John'| date=16 March 2015| accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> After being asked during an interview with CNN if he supported having children through IVF, Dolce replied, \"Yeah, I don't have anything bad, because the beauty of the world is freedom...We love gay couple. We are gay. We love gay couple. We love gay adoption. We love everything. It's just an express of my private point of view.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/18/world/dolce-gabbana-ivf/| newspaper=CNN| title=CNN Exclusive: Dolce & Gabbana: We don't judge on IVF| first=Anna Coren |last=Madison Park|date= 18 March 2015| accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/dolce--gabbana-slam-boycott-5359770 |newspaper=Daily Mirror | title=Dolce & Gabbana slam boycott campaign over IVF and adoption row as 'medieval' | first=Charlotte | last=Wareing |date=18 March 2015 | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Shanghai event promotion video ===\n[[File:D&G Using Chopsticks to Eat Italian Foods.png|thumb|200px|The first video lectures the lady should use ''this stick shaped silverware like pliers'' to eat pizza. Episode 1: ''Pizza Margherita'']]\nIn November 2018, Dolce & Gabbana released a series of videos on [[Instagram]], [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] profiles, as well as its [[Sina Weibo]] account in China, featuring a Chinese model with her eye intentionally narrowed <ref>{{cite web |title=DG\u8fb1\u534e\u5e7f\u544a\u6a21\u7279\u5de6\u4e5f\u6545\u610f\u5316\u5986\u5c0f\u773c\uff1f\u5de6\u4e5f\u5e94\u8be5\u4e3a\u89c6\u9891\u9053\u6b49\u5417\uff1f|trans-title= Model Zuo Ye from D&G Chinese insulting commercial has been intentionally shrinked her eyes? Should she apologize for the video?|url=http://www.hxnews.com/news/yule/201811/24/1657224.shtml|website=\u6d77\u5ce1\u7f51|date=24 November 2018|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>, dressed up in the brand's garments and accessories and clumsily attempting to use [[chopstick]]s to eat Italian food in a pretentious way. The video narratage is in [[Standard Mandarin]] with a hubristic and lecturing tone, while having [[sexual suggestiveness|sexually suggestive]] lines.<ref>{{cite web |title=D&G\u4e8b\u4ef6\uff1a\u5f53\u4e1c\u65b9\u4e0d\u518d\u63a5\u53d7\u897f\u65b9\u7684\u5ba1\u7f8e\"\u9a6f\u5316\" |trans-title= When the East is no longer accepting the 'acclimatization' of the Western views of beauty|url=https://wallstreetcn.com/articles/3442931 |website=Wall Street China|date=24 November 2018 |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=D&G\uff1a\"\u81f4\u656c\u4e2d\u56fd\"\u4e3a\u4f55\u641e\u7838\uff1f|trans-title= Why 'In honor of China' is screwed up?|url=http://www.ftchinese.com/story/001080350?full=y&archive |website=FT Chinese |date=23 November 2018|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> These videos were intended to promote \"The Great Show\", a catwalk event to be held at Expo Center of [[Shanghai]], [[China]] on 21 November. Social media users commented that it reflects Dolce & Gabbana's lack of understanding of Chinese culture and [[racism]]. Under the public pressure, D&G removed this series from its Sina Weibo whilst still keeping them on Instagram.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/dolce-gabbana-faces-blacklash-china-racist-ads-remarks-instagram-170723228.html|title=Dolce & Gabbana faces backlash in China over 'racist' ads and remarks on Instagram and Youtube|last=Hu|first=Krystal|date=21 November 2018|publisher=Yahoo! Finance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121214516/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/dolce-gabbana-faces-blacklash-china-racist-ads-remarks-instagram-170723228.html|archivedate=21 November 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> Social media outcry was further exacerbated by a screen capture of racist comments alleged to have been made by D&G co-founder, Stefano Gabbana, in a direct message on Instagram to an American fashion blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/chinese-model-thought-career-was-over-after-racist-dolce-and-gabbana-ad|title=Chinese model thought career was over after 'racist' Dolce and Gabbana ad|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref> Stefano Gabbana complained about removing the videos from the internet and called China the \"Ignorant Dirty Smelling Mafia\", adding that it was a \"country of shit\" in the message.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/5462653/dolce-gabbana-apology-insensitive-china-ads/|title=Dolce & Gabbana Issues Apology to China After Backlash Over Ads|last=Martinez|first=Gina|date=24 November 2018|website=Time|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-24/dolce-&-gabbana-founders-apologise-for-china-racism-incident/10551342|title=Dolce & Gabbana apologises over China racism furore|date=2018-11-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2174382/celebrities-and-models-boycott-dolce-and-gabbana-show-china-over|title=Celebrities boycott Dolce & Gabbana show in China over 'racist outburst'|date=2018-11-21|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref> Later Dolce & Gabbana claimed on Instagram that both the brand's and the designer's accounts had been hacked. [[Wang Junkai]] and [[Dilraba Dilmurat]], both of whom served as the brand's celebrity ambassadors, severed their ties with the company. Other celebrities, including [[Zhang Ziyi]], [[Li Bingbing]] and [[Chen Kun]] withdrew from the event. Ultimately, the show was cancelled by the brand.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/20/dolce-and-gabbana-accused-of-racism-in-chinese-chopsticks-ads.html | newspaper=CNBC | title=Dolce and Gabbana reportedly cancels Shanghai fashion show after racism accusations | last=Handley | first=Lucy | date=20 November 2018 | accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/style/fashion-beauty/article/2174362/dolce-gabbanas-shanghai-show-cancelled-amid | newspaper=South China Morning Post | title=Dolce & Gabbana's Shanghai show is cancelled amid accusations of racism in 'Chinese chopsticks' ad campaign |  last=Liu | first=Leona | date=21 November 2018 | accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/dolce-gabbana-shanghai-controversy/index.html | newspaper=CNN | title=Dolce & Gabbana cancels China show amid 'racist' ad controversy | last=Chung | first=Stephy| last2=Holland | first2=Oscar  | date=21 November 2018 | accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2174675/dolce-gabbana-founders-ask-chinese-people-forgiveness-after|title=Dolce & Gabbana founders beg Chinese people\u2019s forgiveness|date=2018-11-23|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\nChinese e-commerce sites, including [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]] and [[JD.com]], removed the products of Dolce & Gabbana.<ref name=wp201811>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinese-campaign-to-boycott-dolce-and-gabbana-mounts-as-co-founders-issue-apology/2018/11/23/2ff1e69e-ef07-11e8-9236-bb94154151d2_story.html?noredirect=on | newspaper=The Washington Post | title=Chinese campaign to boycott Dolce & Gabbana mounts as co-founders issue apology | last=Shin | first=Gerry  | date=23 November 2018 | accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> The founders of Dolce & Gabbana apologized in a video on 23 November, which was posted on its Sina Weibo account, and also posted on Instagram and Facebook later. Throughout the video, the founders can be seen reading off a script from a teleprompter located on the right. At the end of the video, the founders were saying \"\u5bf9\u4e0d\u8d77\" (sorry) in Chinese. Meanwhile, the three videos were finally removed from the official Instagram account.<ref name=wp201811/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/dolce-gabbana-founders-make-video-apology-china-after-racism-accusations-n939461| publisher=NBC News | title=Dolce & Gabbana founders make video apology to China after racism accusations | date=23 November 2018 | accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-46968750|title=Model reveals pain of 'racist' D&G ad|date=2019-01-23|access-date=2019-08-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n\nIn their Spring/Summer 2013 collection they included earrings and fabric prints that to American audiences closely resembled imagery associated with the [[Mammy archetype]] with many media outlets commenting the likeness. The designs, however, were intended to make reference to Sicilian Moor's heads, popular good luck charms in Sicilian folklore.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://jezebel.com/5946724/dolce--gabbana-shows-racist-mammy-earrings-and-fun-fabric-prints | newspaper=Jezebel | title=Dolce & Gabbana Shows Racist 'Mammy' Earrings and Fabric Prints | first=Jenna | last=Sauers | date=27 September 2012 | accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2016, the brand came under fire for a listing on their web store of a pair of sandals featuring colorful decorations and pom poms with the title of \"Slave Sandal in Napa Leather\". Other retailers listed them as the Bianca or the Pom Pom sandal. Sandals in Italy are often referred to as such in reference to Ancient Rome. When social media users called the name into question, the listing was changed.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/fashion/dolce-gabbana-release-offensive-slave-sandal-article-1.2551821 | newspaper=New York Daily News | title=Dolce & Gabbana release offensive 'Slave Sandal' as part of Spring 2016 collection | first=Nicole | last=Bitette | date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\n\nIn May 2009, the [[Italian government]] charged Dolce & Gabbana with [[tax evasion]] for having moved assets of about 249 million euros to [[Luxembourg]] in the 2004\u20132006 period.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://mazzetta.splinder.com/post/20651674/Dolce+%26+Gabbana+tentano+l%27evas | title = D&G tentano l'evasione del secolo | work = Mazzetta blog | date = 31 May 2009 | accessdate = 31 May 2009 }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ilgiornale.it/a.pic1?ID=353960 | title = Pi\u00f9 Gabbana che Dolce Perch\u00e9 i giornali ignorano quella notizia |work=Il Giornale |language=Italian | date = 26 May 2009 | accessdate =31 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2013, they were found guilty of failing to declare 1 billion euros ($1.3 billion) of income to authorities after moving their brand to [[Gado (company)|Gado]], a Luxembourg-based [[holding company]]. The court sentenced them both to one year and eight months in jail.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://business.time.com/2013/06/19/dolce-and-gabbana-convicted-of-tax-evasion/#ixzz2Wg0MuLJt | title = Dolce and Gabbana Convicted of Tax Evasion | work = Time | date = 19 June 2013 | accessdate = 19 June 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130622063541/http://business.time.com/2013/06/19/dolce-and-gabbana-convicted-of-tax-evasion/#ixzz2Wg0MuLJt | archivedate = 22 June 2013 }}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana were quick to file a 90-page appeal and thus did not face any jail time.\n\nOn 30 April 2014, a three judge panel overruled the appeal and decided to uphold the initial sentence.<ref name=\"Dolce, Gabbana Found Guilty of Tax Evasion\">{{cite web | url=http://www.businessoffashion.com/2014/04/dolce-gabbana-appeal-denied-guilty-tax-evasion.html | title=Dolce, Gabbana Found Guilty of Tax Evasion | publisher=Business of Fashion | date=30 April 2014 | accessdate=7 May 2014 | author=Wang, Lisa}}</ref> However, since they were sentenced to only one year and six months, which is under the two-year minimum, both of them will not serve actual imprisonment in jail.<ref name=\"Dolce, Gabbana Found Guilty of Tax Evasion\"/>\n\nOn 24 October 2014, both Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana were found innocent of tax evasion by the [[Italian Court of Justice]].<ref name=\"Robert Wood\">{{cite news \n| last= Wood \n| first= Robert W. \n| url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/robertwood/2014/10/25/dolce-gabbana-cleared-of-tax-evasion-could-help-lionel-messi-trial/\n| title= Dolce & Gabbana Cleared Of Tax Evasion, Could Help Lionel Messi Trial\n| publisher= forbes.com\n| date= 25 October 2014\n| accessdate= \n}}</ref> After the court's decision was announced, Stefano Gabbana tweeted in Italian, \"We knew it!!! We are honest people!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/591768/dolce-gabbana-founders-found-innocent-in-tax-evasion-case-we-knew-it-we-are-honest-people|title=Dolce & Gabbana Founders Found Innocent in Tax Evasion Case |work=E! Online}}</ref><ref name=\"LUKE LEITCH\">{{cite news \n| last= LEITCH\n| first= LUKE \n| url= http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG11186176/Dolce-and-Gabbana-cleared-of-tax-evasion.html\n| title= Dolce and Gabbana cleared of tax evasion: Rome's supreme court overturned a ruling that found designers Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana guilty of tax evasion with a 20-month prison penalty\n| publisher= telegraph.co.uk\n| date= 24 October 2014\n| accessdate= \n}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* \"Dolce & Gabbana.\" The Thames & Hudson Dictionary of Fashion and Fashion Designers. London: Thames & Hudson, 2007. Credo Reference. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"Gabbana, Stefano.\" Marquis Who's Who in the World. New Providence: Marquis Who's Who LLC, 2011. Credo Reference. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"Gabbana, Stefano.\" The Thames & Hudson Dictionary of Fashion and Fashion Designers. London: Thames & Hudson, 2007. Credo Reference. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"[http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/domenico-dolce-quotes/2011/6/2 Domenico Dolce Quotes \u2013 Swide Magazine].\" Swide Magazine by Dolce&Gabbana. Swide Magazine, 2 June 2011. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20150227211103/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/dolce-gabbana.html Dolce & Gabbana \u2013 Biography on Bio].\" Bio: Shows, Video, TV Schedule and More on Bio. AETN UK. Web. 29 November 2011.\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Dolce & Gabbana}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.dolcegabbana.com/}}\n* {{Fashionlabel|id=dolce-gabbana}}\n* [https://www.fashion.net/dolce-gabbana Dolce & Gabbana on FASHION NET]\n<!--==========================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS NOR SHOULD IT BE USED FOR ADVERTISING. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===========================-->\n\n{{Designer labels}}\n{{Men's undergarments}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolce and Gabbana}}\n[[Category:Dolce & Gabbana| ]]\n[[Category:Italian fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of Italy]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Shoe companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:High fashion brands]]\n[[Category:Luxury brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Milan]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Design companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Bags (fashion)]]\n[[Category:Underwear brands]]\n[[Category:Watch manufacturing companies of Italy]]\n[[Category:Italian brands]]\n[[Category:Eyewear brands of Italy]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect2|D & G|Gabbana|the region in Scotland|Dumfries and Galloway|the fashion designer|Stefano Gabbana|the Jamaican beverage company|Desnoes & Geddes}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{coord|45.469045|9.2072378|display=title}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Dolce & Gabbana S.R.L.\n| logo = [[File:Dolce and Gabbana.svg|225px]]\n| caption = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-2 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{Tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| type = [[Societ\u00e0 a Responsabilit\u00e0 Limitata#Italy|Societ\u00e0 a responsabilit\u00e0 limitata]]\n| traded_as = \n| industry = Luxury retail\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1985|df=yes}}<br>[[Milan]], Italy\n| founders = [[Domenico Dolce]]<br> [[Stefano Gabbana]]\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location = Milan\n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Alfonso Dolce, CEO|Cristiana Ruella, COO}}\n| products = Clothing, footwear, handbags, sunglasses, watches, jewellery, perfumes and cosmetics\n| production = \n| services = \n| revenue = \u20ac1.29 billion (2017/2018)<ref name=\"businessinsider\">{{cite news |last=Scozzari |first=Carlotta |date=5 September 2018 |title=Il 2018 di Dolce & Gabbana: fatturato stabile, utile gi\u00f9 e niente dividendo per i due soci |url=https://it.businessinsider.com/i-conti-di-dolce-gabbana-fatturato-stabile-utile-giu-e-niente-dividendo-per-i-due-soci/ |work=Business Insider Italia |language=Italian}}</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \u20ac60.5 million<ref name=\"businessinsider\"/>\n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 3,150\n| parent = Dolce & Gabbana Luxembourg S.\u00e0.r.l.\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| footnotes = \n| location_country = Italy\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.dolcegabbana.com/}}\n| romanized = \n| former type = \n| intl = \n| bodystyle = \n}}\n'''Dolce & Gabbana''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8dolt\u0283e e \u0261ab\u02c8ba\u02d0na}})<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=d\u00f3lce |url=https://www.dizionario-italiano.it/dizionario-italiano.php?lemma=DOLCE100 |encyclopedia=Dizionario Italiano |language=Italian |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite encyclopedia |title=gabb\u00e0na |url=https://www.dizionario-italiano.it/dizionario-italiano.php?lemma=GABBANA100 |encyclopedia=Dizionario Italiano |language=Italian |access-date=29 May 2019}}</ref> is an Italian [[Luxury goods|luxury]] [[fashion house]]<ref name=\"Vernon\">{{cite news | url = http://observer.guardian.co.uk/focus/story/0,6903,1418537,00.html | title = Mixing business and pleasure | date = 20 February 2005 | accessdate = 27 July 2007 | last = Vernon | first = Polly | location = London | work = The Guardian }}</ref> founded in 1985 in [[Legnano]] by Italian designers [[Domenico Dolce]] and [[Stefano Gabbana]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/dolce-gabbana_(Dizionario-di-Economia-e-Finanza)/ | work=Dizionario di Economia e Finanza \u2013 Enciclopedia italiana | date= | accessdate=17 November 2014 | title=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n\nThe two met in [[Milan]] in 1980 and designed for the same fashion house. In 1982, they established a designer consulting studio; in time it grew to become \"Dolce & Gabbana\". They presented their first women's collection in 1985<ref name=Givhan2012>{{cite news|last=Givhan|first=Robin|title=Ob-la-di, Ob-la-da, Bras Go On|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/03/18/the-evolution-of-the-bra-from-mad-men-s-day-to-our-own.html|accessdate=15 October 2012|newspaper=Newsweek|date=2 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927215141/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2012/03/18/the-evolution-of-the-bra-from-mad-men-s-day-to-our-own.html|archive-date=27 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> in Milan, where a year later their store would open its doors.\n\nIn 1988, they launched a leotard line, and in 1989 they began designing underwear and swimming costumes. Dolce & Gabbana started to export their products to Japan and other countries including the United States, where they founded their own showroom in 1990. In 1992, the same year they presented their men's collection, they also launched their first perfume Dolce & Gabbana. They won the [[Woolmark]] award in 1991, and Perfume's Academy \"Most Feminine Flavor of the Year\" in 1993 for their fragrance Dolce & Gabbana Parfum. By the end of the 1990s, the company's revenues were around [[United States dollar|US$]]500&nbsp;million and in 2003 their revenue reached $633&nbsp;million. By 2005, their turnover was [[Euro|\u20ac]]600 million.<ref name=\"Vogue.com UK\">{{cite web | title = Who's Who \u2013 Dolce & Gabbana Biography | work = Vogue UK | url = http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/080421-dolce--gabbana-biography.aspx | accessdate = 27 May 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080907145531/http://www.vogue.co.uk/biographies/080421-dolce--gabbana-biography.aspx | archivedate = 7 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== The design house ==\n\n=== Early collections ===\nThe first collection from the design duo was shown in October 1985<ref name=\"Givhan2012\"/><ref name=BPRT>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=H5oadQtleT4C&pg=PA206&dq=history+of+dolce+and+gabbana+collections#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20dolce%20and%20gabbana%20collections&f=false |title=The Great Fashion Designers |author=Brenda Polan and Roger Trendre |year=2009 |publisher=Berg |page=206|isbn=9781847882271 }}</ref> alongside five other up-and-coming Italian labels as part of [[Milan Fashion Week]]. The two did not have enough money to hire models or provide accessories for them, so they sought help from their friends. The models (their friends) simply wore their personal items to complement the clothing. They used a bed sheet that Dolce had brought from home as their stage curtain.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/07/16/dolce.gabbana.interview/index.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana: Fashion's golden duo |date=21 July 2012 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |publisher=[[CNN International]] |author=Stefanie Blendis and Gisella Deputato}}</ref>\n\nThe pair labeled their first collection ''Real Women'', due in part to the use of local women as models on the runway.<ref name=BPRT /> Sales from their first collection were disappointing enough for Gabbana to cancel the fabric order they'd put in to create their second collection. However, Dolce's family offered to help meet their costs when the two visited them in [[Sicily]] over Christmas, while incidentally, the fabric company did not receive the cancellation notice in time so the fabric was ready for them back in Milan upon their return.<ref name=TNY>{{cite news |title=Hands and Eyes: When Dolce met Gabbana |author= John Seabrook |publisher=[[The New Yorker]]| date=14 March 2005 |url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2005/03/14/050314fa_fact1?currentPage=all}}</ref> They produced the next collection in 1986 and opened their first store that same year.<ref name=BPRT /> [[Michael Gross (writer)|Michael Gross]] wrote of their third collection in a 1992 interview, \"They were a secret known only to a handful of Italian fashion editors. Their few models changed behind a rickety screen. They called their collection of T-shirt-cotton and elastic-silk pieces, Transformation.\" The clothing in this collection came with instructions on the seven different ways a piece could be worn in an outfit, as the wearer could use [[Velcro]] and snaps to alter the clothing's form.<ref name=MGNYM />\n\nTheir fourth collection was the first to make a significant impact on the Italian fashion market. In this collection, Dolce drew upon his Sicilian roots. The collection's advertising campaign was shot by photographer [[Ferdinando Scianna]] in Sicily, and featured Dutch model [[Marpessa Hennink]] in black and white pictures<ref name=italia>{{cite journal|last1=Locatelli|first1=Rossella|title=Marpessa - Vogue Italia Encyclo|journal=Vogue Italia|url=http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/people/m/marpessa|accessdate=7 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411185716/http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/people/m/marpessa|archive-date=11 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=clase>{{cite journal|last1=Mu\u00f1oz Martinez-Mora|first1=Ines|title=Marpessa Clase Superior|journal=Vogue Espa\u00f1a|date=May 2013|pages=206\u2013216|trans-title=Marpessa Top Class|language=Spanish}}</ref> inspired by the Italian cinema of the 1940s. They continued the use of Italian cinema as inspiration in their fifth collection, drawing on the work of filmmaker [[Luchino Visconti]] and his film ''[[The Leopard (1963 film)|The Leopard]]''.<ref name=BPRT />\n\nOne of the pieces from their fourth collection was labeled \"The Sicilian Dress\" by the fashion press, and was named by author Hal Rubenstein as one of the 100 most important dresses ever designed. It is considered to be the most representative piece of this era for the brand. Rubenstein described the piece in 2012 by writing, \"The Sicilian dress is the essence of Dolce & Gabbana, the brand's sartorial touchstone. The dress takes its cue from a slip\u2014but it's a slip that's adorned [[Anna Magnani]], and it's a silhouette that has graced [[Anita Ekberg]], [[Sophia Loren]], [and so forth]. The straps fit tight to the body just as bra straps would; the neckline runs straight across but gets waylaid at least twice, once on each side to caress each breast and in the middle to meet an uplifting tuck that's giving a gentle push up. The slip doesn't just slide down, but comes in at the waist to hold the figure firmly but not too tightly and then widens to emphasise the hips, only to fall with a slight taper at the knees to guarantee that the hips will sway when the wearer walks.\"<ref name=HB>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KvzSrWl5QP0C&pg=PT202&dq=dolce+and+gabbana+collection#v=onepage&q=dolce%20and%20gabbana%20collection&f=false |title=100 Unforgettable Dresses |author=Hal Rubenstein |publisher=Harper Collins |year=2012|isbn=9780062198884 }}</ref>\n\n=== The 1980s and 1990s ===\nIn 1987, the two launched a separate knitwear line and in 1989, they started designing a lingerie line and a beachwear line. Two years later, they launched their leotard line. In 1989, Dolce & Gabbana opened their first store in Japan in partnership with Kashiyama Co. They started to export their products to the United States, where they founded their own showroom in 1990. In 1992, the same year that they presented their men\u2019s collection, they also launched their first perfume Dolce & Gabbana. They won an \u201cOscar des Parfums\u201d for best male perfume in 1996 from the French Parfum Academy, the first time ever that the title has been awarded to an Italian brand. Towards the end of the 1990s their sales were around $500 million and in 2003 alone, their revenue reached $633.2 million.\nIn 1990, they launched their first men's collection.<ref name=VSB /> That year, they also moved the design house into its first official offices and began to design gowns and other more expensive pieces in addition to their original clothing.<ref name=MGNYM /> Their 1990 Spring/Summer women's collection referenced the mythological painting of [[Raphael]], and the duo began to build a reputation for crystal-encrusted clothing. The 1991 Fall/Winter women's collection was also adorned by trinkets, including [[filigree]] medals and embellished [[corset]]s. The 1992 Fall/Winter women's collection was then inspired by the silver screen of the 1950s, though the collection still included crystal embellished body suits.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-archive-embellishments/2011/11/27 |work=Swide Magazine |date=27 November 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=Dolce & Gabbana and their Private Renaissance |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, their men's collection was awarded the Woolmark Award for the most innovative men's collection of the year.<ref name=BIOCH /> What is considered to be their first foray into international recognition came when [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] wore a corset made of gemstones and an accompanying jacket from Dolce & Gabbana at the 1991 [[New York City]] premiere of ''[[Madonna: Truth or Dare|Truth or Dare]]: In Bed with Madonna''. The duo then partnered with Madonna in 1993 to design over 1500 costumes for the artist's ''[[Girlie Show]]'' international tour in support of her 1992 album ''[[Erotica (Madonna album)|Erotica]]''.<ref name=VSB>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=Hemsvn9ZbRkC&pg=PA224&dq=history+of+dolce+and+gabbana+collections#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20dolce%20and%20gabbana%20collections&f=false |pages=223\u2013225 |title=The Berg Companion to Fashion |author=Valerie Steele |publisher=Berg |year=2010 |accessdate=3 May 2012|isbn=9781847885920 }}</ref> In an interview about the costumes, Madonna stated that, \"Their clothes are sexy with a sense of humor\u2014like me.\"<ref name=MGNYM>{{cite news |author=Michael Gross |title=La Dolce (& Gabbana) Vita |work=[[New York Magazine]] |date=7 September 1992 |pages=16\u201317}}</ref> In 1994, the house's trademark [[double-breasted]] jacket was named \"La Turlington\" after model [[Christy Turlington]]. That same year the company launched its second main line\u2014D&G, a line aimed at younger individuals. In 1996 the D&G runway show was streamed only on the Internet and not the runway, in an experimental move towards new media. That year Dolce & Gabbana also designed the costumes for the film ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]''.<ref name=VGP />\n\nIn the film industry, both Dolce & Gabbana appeared in the 1995 film ''[[The Star Maker (1995 film)|The Star Maker]] (L'Uomo delle Stelle)'' by director [[Giuseppe Tornatore]], playing minor roles as extras. They appeared in more significant cameo roles in [[Rob Marshall]]'s film-adaptation of ''[[Nine (2009 live-action film)|Nine]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.graziadaily.co.uk/fashion/archive/2009/12/03/dolce---gabbana-turn-film-stars.htm |work=Grazia Daily |date=3 December 2009 |author=Angela Bottolph |accessdate=29 May 2012 |title=Dolce & Gabbana turn film stars!}}</ref> As stylists, they also worked on the music video ''[[All You Need Is Now|Girl Panic!]]'' by [[Duran Duran]].<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |title=Supermodel Summit |author=Lauren Milligan |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2011/06/13/supermodels-in-duran-duran-video-dolce-and-gabbana |date=13 June 2011 |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn terms of market expansion, in 1989 Dolce & Gabbana signed an agreement with the Kashiyama group to open their first boutique in Japan. They released their first fragrance for women in 1992, called \"Dolce & Gabbana Pour Femme\", which was awarded the Perfume Academy's 1993 award for best feminine fragrance of the year. Their first male fragrance, \"Dolce & Gabbana pour Homme\", was the recipient of the best masculine fragrance of the year award from the same Academy in 1995.<ref name=BIOCH>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/dolce-gabbana.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana |accessdate=29 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815181601/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/dolce-gabbana.html |archivedate=15 August 2012 }}</ref> That year Dolce & Gabbana's collections caused a controversy with the British and Italian press, when they selected the American gangster motif as inspiration for their work.<ref>{{cite book |page=19 |title=Fashion at the Edge: Spectacle, Modernity, and Deathliness |author=Caroline Evans |publisher=Yale University Press |year=2003}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana transposed this Fall/Winter 1995 inspiration onto women's wear, which critics stated brought an erotic edge to the clothing. The duo had used the motif before in 1992 when photographer [[Steven Meisel]] shot an ad campaign for the house in which the models posed in \"gangster chic\". This included wide-lapelled 1930s style coats and black leather caps.<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashion, Desire and Anxiety: Image and Morality in the 20th Century |pages=39\u201340 |author=Rebecca Arnold |year=2001 |publisher=I.B. Tauris}}</ref>\n\nAuthor Nirupama Pundir stated that, \"Dolce & Gabbana, with their superfeminine and fantastical style, broke away from the serious and sober-minded fashions that dominated during much of the Nineties.\"<ref>{{cite book |page=40 |title=Fashion Technology: Today And Tomorrow |author=Nirupama Pundir |publisher=Mittal Publications |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\nDolce & Gabbana continued to work with Madonna, designing the costumes for her [[Drowned World Tour]] in 2001, in support of her 2000 album ''[[Music (Madonna album)|Music]]''.<ref name=VGP>{{cite web |url=http://www.vogue.com/voguepedia/Dolce_%26_Gabbana |title=Dolce & Gabbana |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> They also designed costumes for the international tours of [[Missy Elliott]], [[Beyonc\u00e9]], and [[Mary J. Blige]].<ref name=VGP /><ref>{{cite book |page=55 |title= Cherry Bomb: The Ultimate Guide to Becoming a Better Flirt, a Tougher Chick, and a Hotter Girlfriend\u2014and to Living Life Like a Rock Star |publisher=Simon & Schuster |author=Carrie Bornillo-Vrenna |year=2008}}</ref> In 1999, the duo appeared on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' in support of singer [[Whitney Houston]], who used the show to debut the Dolce & Gabbana designed costumes for her ''[[My Love Is Your Love]]'' tour, considered by fashion and music critics to be unusually ''risqu\u00e9''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elle.com/Pop-Culture/Celebrity-Spotlight/Looking-Back-at-Whitney-Houston/(imageIndex)/14/(play)/false#mode=base;slide=14; |title=Looking Back at Whitney Houston |author=Britt Aboutaleb |date=13 February 2012 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]] }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The duo continued to design costumes for musical artists through the 2000s, including the costumes for [[Kylie Minogue]]'s [[Showgirl Homecoming]] tour.<ref name=VGP /> Madonna also participated in Dolce & Gabbana's 2010 advertising campaigns.<ref name=HB />\n\nIn the 2000s, Dolce & Gabbana took a great deal of inspiration from the sport of football as well. In 2003 the men's line took its main inspiration from the world's great football stars.<ref name=VSB /> Other forms of art began taking inspirations from Dolce & Gabbana too. In 2003 dance music artist [[Frankie Knuckles]] said that the fashion house was a \"great barometer\" for trends in both fashion and music.<ref>{{cite news |date=8 November 2003 |work=[[Billboard Magazine]] |author=Michale Paoletta |title=Armani Conjures 'Night' for its Second A/X Disc |page=28}}</ref> As for their impact on the design world, in 2002 the corsets that were a key part of Dolce & Gabbana's early designs were revived by many of Europe's main designers as a trend.<ref>{{cite news |page=74 |work=Out Magazine |title=A model designers |date=March 2002 |author=Brendan Lemon}}</ref> In recent years Dolce & Gabbana has begun holding private viewings of their new collections for buyers, in order to sell their collections before they become public and to pre-empt the copying of their designs by [[Fast fashion|fast fashion companies]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Beating the Commodity Trap: How to Maximize Your Competitive Position and Increase Your Pricing Power |author=Richard A. D'Aveni |publisher=Harvard Business Press |year=2009 |page=34}}</ref>\n\nBy 2005 their turnover was \u20ac597 million.<ref name=\"Vogue.com UK\"/> In 2006, the company started a new journey in accessories and leather goods for men and women. The company also ventured into cosmetics, with Scarlett Johansson as the face of the advertising campaign.\n[[File:Dolce e Gabbana (26441884825).jpg|thumb|Stefano Gabbana (left) and Domenico Dolce (right) in 2016]]\nIn 2012, D&G was merged with Dolce & Gabbana in order to strengthen the main line. The final independent D&G collection was the Spring/Summer 2012 collection shown in September 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2011/03/03/dolce-and-gabbana-considers-merging-dandg-line |title=The End of D&G |work=[[Vogue UK]] |author=Ella Alexander |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> ''[[The New Yorker]]'' published in 2005 that, \"Dolce and Gabbana are becoming to the two-thousands what [[Prada]] was to the nineteen-nineties and Armani was to the nineteen-eighties\u2014''gli stilisti'' whose sensibility defines the decade.\"<ref name=TNY /> As for personal awards, in both 1996 and 1997 Dolce & Gabbana were named by ''[[FHM]]'' as the designers of the year. In 2003 ''[[GQ Magazine]]'' named Dolce & Gabbana among their \"Men of the Year\". The following year readers of ''[[Elle (magazine)|British Elle]]'' voted Dolce & Gabbana the best international designers at the 2004 Elle Style Awards.<ref name=AWD>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbana.com/corporate/en/history/international-awards.html |title=International Awards |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana celebrated the 20th anniversary of their brand on 19 June 2010 at the Piazza della la Scala and [[Palazzo Marino]] in Milan. A public exhibition was also held the following day that included a room in which several dozen televisions were piled haphazardly upon each other, each showing a different collection from the design house's twenty-year history.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dolce&Gabbana 20th Anniversary. A day in history. A video. |author=Dolce & Gabbana |publisher=Youtube: Dolce & Gabbana Channel |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9k3c0DtbiZw |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Brands ==\n[[File:D&G Golden Sneakers.jpg|thumb|A pair of Dolce & Gabbana's Golden Sneakers.]]\nDolce & Gabbana had two central lines (D&G and Dolce&Gabbana) until 2012, when the lines merged under the label Dolce & Gabbana.\n\n=== Dolce&Gabbana ===\nDolce&Gabbana (spelled without spaces, unlike the name of the company) specialises in luxury items inspired by high-designs and is more formal and 'timeless', responding to long-term trends as well as seasonal changes.<ref name=AAB>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Hemsvn9ZbRkC&pg=PA225&dq=Dolce%26Gabbana++rather+than+seasonal+changes#v=onepage&q=Dolce%26Gabbana%20%20rather%20than%20seasonal%20changes&f=false |title=The Berg Companion to Fashion |author=Valerie Steele |publisher=Berg |page=225 |year=2010|isbn=9781847885920 }}</ref> \nIn February 2010, it was announced that American singer [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] would design a collection of sunglasses titled ''MDG'', set to be released in May of that year.\nIt also offers fragrances for men and women. An example is 'The One' which is a perfume by Dolce&Gabbana.\n\n=== D & G ===\nD & G was the younger, more flamboyant [[diffusion line]] of the brand. Unlike Dolce&Gabbana, D&G sold [[watches]] as well as clothing: watches were manufactured by Naloni and [[Binda Group]]. In 2011, Dolce & Gabbana decided to discontinue the D & G-line in order to put \"more strength and energy\" into their other collections.<ref name=\"NY Mag\">{{cite journal| url=http://NY Mag.com/daily/fashion/2012/06/dolce-gabbana-to-launch-couture-on-july-9.html| title=Dolce & Gabbana to launch Couture| journal=NY Mag| accessdate=29 June 2012}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Other lines ===\nDolce & Gabbana created a [[Wedding dress|bridal]] collection, but only between 1992 and 1998. The Dolce & Gabbana Home Collection\u2014started in 1994\u2014was also discontinued in 1999, with the exception of unique pieces being created for D&G premises. The first women's beachwear collection was developed in 1989, followed by the first men's beachwear collection in 1992. D&G launched an eyewear line in 1998 and a timepieces line in 2000. That same year D&G launched both a men's and women's underwear collection, separate from their Dolce & Gabbana lingerie collection. In 2001 they launched the D&G Junior line for children. In 2006 the duo launched the Anamalier line of leopard print accessories for women, and in 2007 they launched a line of [[crocodile]] travel cases for men. Other bags produced by the house include the Miss Sicily tote bag,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.com/vogue-daily/article/editors-eye-february/ |title=Editors' Eye: The Ten Things We Loved (or Longed For) This February |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |author=Tabitha Simmons |work=[[Vogue UK]]}}</ref> and the \"Dolce\" bag, offered in straw and leather.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.glamour.com/fashion/blogs/slaves-to-fashion/2012/01/it-bag-alert-dolce-gabbanas-do.html |title=Celebrity Obsession Alert: Dolce & Gabbana's \"Dolce\" Bag Is Everything For Spring |date=27 January 2012 |work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]] |author=Tracy Lomrantz}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 they launched their first line of color cosmetics,<ref name=DGGH /> with [[Scarlett Johansson]] as the face of the advertising campaign.<ref name=Scarl /> Dolce & Gabbana launched its first line of fine jewellery in late 2011 with an 80-piece line including bejewelled rosaries, charm bracelets, and necklaces.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/jewellery/news/2011/11/9/dolce-and-gabbana-launch-fine-jewellery |work=[[Vogue UK]] |author=Lisa Niven |date=9 November 2011 |title=Dolce's Jewels |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> They later launched a fine jewellery collection for men.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfluxe.net/fit-for-a-king-dolce-gabbanas-fine-jewelry/|title=\u00bb Fit For a King: Dolce & Gabbana's Fine Jewellery Collection|last=Matthews|first=Damion|date=12 November 2015|website=SFLUXE|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana have received several awards for their fragrances, as was described in the above sections. Their current fragrances include: \"The One\", \"Sport\", \"[[Light Blue (fragrance)|Light Blue]]\", \"Dolce\", \"Classic\", \"Sicily\", \"The One Rose\", and the original scents \"Pour Homme\" and \"Parfum\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/dg/perfumes/ |title=Perfumes |accessdate=31 May 2012}}</ref> On 16 October 2014, the company announced that [[Colin Farrell]] would be the face of their new fragrance called \"Intenso.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/2014/10/16/colin-farrell-face-of-dolce-and-gabbana-campaign|title=Colin Farrell, Face Of Dolce & Gabbana Campaign (Vogue.co.uk)|work=Vogue UK}}</ref>\n\n=== Internet ===\nDolce & Gabbana made the \"DG\" logo an iconic and instantly recognizable symbol,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.famouslogos.net/dolce-gabbana-logo/ | title = Dolce & Gabbana Logo&nbsp;\u2013 Design and History | work = FamousLogos.net | accessdate =7 May 2011}}</ref> but they were never able to get the matching internet address DG.com.\nIn fact, DG.com is one of the oldest Internet domains and was already registered in 1986 by the computer company [[Data General]], now defunct. After that company closed in 1999, the url went to [[EMC Corporation|EMC]] before [[Dollar General]] purchased it in 2010 after a bidding war with Dolce & Gabbana.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wayback Machine: 2/3/11 |url=http://www.dollargeneral.com/ |accessdate=19 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107040228/http://www.dollargeneral.com// |archivedate=7 January 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Partnerships ==\n\n=== Sports ===\nDolce & Gabbana has designed the on-field attire for [[A.C. Milan]] since 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/sport-story-2004/2010/10/2 |title=2004: a soccer obsession is born |date=2 October 2010 |work=Swide Magazine |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In addition to having their on-field uniforms designed by Dolce & Gabbana, A.C. Milan players also dress in team-issued Dolce & Gabbana attire when at official functions off the field.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/grant_wahl/07/28/oguchi.onyewu/ |title=Onyewu finding his way into Milan |author=Grant Wahl |date=28 July 2009 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref> The duo also designed the off-field suits for the [[Italy national football team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/designers/d/dolcegabbana |title=Dolce&Gabbana |author=Sara Pizzi |work=[[Vogue Italia]] |accessdate=29 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113015248/http://www.vogue.it/en/encyclo/designers/d/dolcegabbana |archive-date=13 November 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2010, Dolce & Gabbana signed a three-year deal with the [[Chelsea F.C.]] to design and provide the club's on- and off-field uniforms and attire. The deal included the creation of clothing for female staff members in addition to male staff members and the players themselves. The off-field outfits designed for the club included a dark blue suit featuring the lion symbol on the breast pocket. The designers also re-designed the club's director's lounge and main office reception area.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG7913107/Dolce-and-Gabbana-and-Chelsea-Football-Club.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana and Chelsea Football Club |date=27 July 2012 |author=Hilary Alexander |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820012529/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG7913107/Dolce-and-Gabbana-and-Chelsea-Football-Club.html |archivedate=20 August 2012 }}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana were also the named sponsors of the Milano Thunder Italian Boxing Team.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldseriesboxing.com/teams/milan/information.aspx |accessdate= 29 May 2012 |title= Dolce&Gabbana Milano Thunder Italian Boxing Team |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120629182234/http://www.worldseriesboxing.com/teams/milan/information.aspx |archivedate= 29 June 2012 }}</ref>\n\n=== Products ===\nIn 2006, Dolce & Gabbana partnered with [[Motorola]] to produce the [[Motorola RAZR|Motorola V3i Dolce & Gabbana cellular phone]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/CNet/story?id=2612660#.T8Ua3txYtD0 |date=12 December 2006 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |title=Motorola V3i Dolce & Gabbana |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In 2009, Dolce & Gabbana partnered with [[Sony Mobile Communications|Sony Ericsson]] to produce a version of its Jalou [[Mobile phone|cellular phone]] line with [[Gold#Jewelry|24-karat gold details]] and the logo of the design house emblazoned on the co-designed piece of technology.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://gazetaweb.globo.com/noticia.php?c=7887&e=11 |date=27 October 2009 |work=Gazeta de Algoas |title= Celular Jalou 'veste' Dolce & Gabbana |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana also partnered with [[Citro\u00ebn]] to co-design a version of their [[Citro\u00ebn C3|C3 Pluriel vehicle]].<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.chronica.it/2008/02/27/auto-griffate-non-solo-una-moda-ma-uno-stile-di-vita/ |date=27 February 2008 |title=Auto griffate: non solo una moda, ma uno stile di vita |author=Eleonora Marini |accessdate=29 May 2012 |work=Chronica}}</ref> In 2010 Dolce & Gabbana partnered with [[Martini (vermouth)|Martini]] to produce a \"gold edition\" of its vermouth.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.moetodete.bg/zvezdni-novini/martini-gold-by-dolce-and-gabbana-noviyat-svetski-hit.html |title=Martini Gold by Dolce & Gabbana |publisher=Moetodete.bg |date=23 November 2010 |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> In 2010 the design house then teamed with singer Madonna to release a co-designed line of sunglasses called MDG.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uk.reuters.com/article/2010/03/16/us-fashion-madonna-dolcegabbana-idUKTRE62F3RK20100316 |title=Madonna designs Dolce & Gabbana sunglasses |author=Marie-Louise Gumuchian |date=16 March 2010 |accessdate=29 May 2012 |publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n== Advertising campaigns ==\nThe commercial for the first women fragrance of Dolce & Gabbana ran for several years in Italy, created by filmmaker [[Giuseppe Tornatore]], scored by [[Ennio Morricone]], and starred actress [[Monica Bellucci]]. The 30-second commercial begins with a man slapping an octopus against the stone ridges of a [[tide pool]]. He stands and looks around his surroundings at different women going about their daily lives. One woman (Bellucci) is seen changing into a 1950s-style bathing suit behind a white sheet being held up by two other women. After she changes, she tosses her bra atop a [[Opuntia|prickly pear cactus]] and walks towards the ocean. Later she is seen lying atop a well-made bed, and the man who saw her is standing outside her window, holding her bra up to his nose. The film closes with the image of the Dolce & Gabbana fragrance bottles against a black backdrop.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-video-archive-perfume/2011/10/9 |work=Swide Magazine |date=9 October 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=1994: Monica Bellucci and Giuseppe Tornatore for Dolce & Gabbana |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref> In 2003, the Dolce & Gabbana perfume Sicily was advertised in another commercial about a Sicilian funeral, which was also directed by Giuseppe Tornatore.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-archive-funerale/2011/10/30 |work=Swide Magazine |date=30 October 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=Funeral alla Dolce & Gabbana |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref>\n\n[[Gisele B\u00fcndchen]] starred in the 2006 commercial for the fragrance \"The One\", featuring Bundchen in front of a vanity mirror being made up, with flashes of a mob of cameramen interspersed; she then puts on a golden dress, shoes, and a pair of D&G sunglasses.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/dg-video-archive-the-one/2011/11/13 |work=Swide Magazine |date=13 November 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title=Gisele is The One |author=Valentina Zannoni}}</ref> Photographers and filmmakers that have worked with Dolce & Gabbana on advertising campaigns have included Giampaolo Barbieri,<ref>{{cite news |title=Photo Spread |work=GQ Russia |date=March 2011 |pages=242\u2013245}}</ref> Michel Comte,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.michelcomte.org/index.php/the-artist.html |title=The Artist |accessdate=19 May 2012 |year=2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215192118/http://www.michelcomte.org/index.php/the-artist.html |archivedate=15 February 2010 }}</ref> Fabrizio Ferri,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/Spring-summer-1987----the-power-of-a-DolceGabbana-transformation/2010/6/13 |title=Spring/Summer 1987: The Power of Dolce & Gabbana Transformation |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> [[Steven Klein (photographer)|Steven Klein]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/2009/12/dolce-gabbana-madonna-by-steven-klein-for-dolce-gabbana-ss-2010.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana: Madonna by Steven Klein for Dolce & Gabbana S/S 2010 |work=OhLaLa Magazine |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115050936/http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/2009/12/dolce-gabbana-madonna-by-steven-klein-for-dolce-gabbana-ss-2010.html |archive-date=15 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2007/02/dolce_gabbana#slide=1 |title=Stefano and Domenico's Dolce Vita |work=W Magazine |date=February 2007 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207012423/http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2007/02/dolce_gabbana#slide=1 |archivedate=7 December 2014 }}</ref> [[Steven Meisel]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.designscene.net/2008/06/dolce-gabbana-fall-winter-2006.html |title=Dolce & Gabbana Fall Winter 2006: The Renaissance by Steven Meisel |work=Design Scene |date=13 June 2008 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Mert + Marcus,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/Life/Bellezza/felicity-jones-make-up/2012/2/13 |title=Felicity Jones by Mert+Marcus for Dolce &Gabbana Make-up |work=Swide Magazine |date=13 February 2012}}</ref> [[Jean Baptiste Mondino]],<ref name=Scarl>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch_scarlett_johansson_likes_her_lips_for_kissing_in_dolce_gabbana_ad_by_ |title=Watch: Scarlett Johansson Likes Her Lips For Kissing In Dolce & Gabbana Ad By Jean-Baptiste Mondino |date=24 October 2011 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |author=Kevin Jagernauth |publisher=Indiewire |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227181743/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch_scarlett_johansson_likes_her_lips_for_kissing_in_dolce_gabbana_ad_by_ |archive-date=27 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ferdinando Scianna,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.magnumphotos.com/Catalogue/Ferdinando-Scianna/1987/Dutch-model-MARPESSA-photographed-for-DOLCE-_-GABBANA-1987-NN145557.html |title= Ferdinando Scianna \u2013 Dutch model, MARPESSA, photographed for DOLCE & GABBANA. 1987. |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Giampaolo Sgura,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/giampaolo-sgura/ |work= Ohlala Magazine |title= Alfred Kovac & Valerija Sestic For D&G Summer 2012 Eyewear |accessdate= 19 May 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20141204171742/http://www.ohlalamag.com/en/giampaolo-sgura/ |archivedate= 4 December 2014 }}</ref> [[Mario Sorrenti]],<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2008/03/mario_sorrenti#slide=1 |title=On Fire |date=March 2008 |work=W Magazine |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> S\u00f8lve Sundsb\u00f8,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9405E2D6173DF930A1575BC0A96F9C8B63 |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=Pulse; Wearing the Works |author=Karin Nelson |date=23 August 2009 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> [[Mario Testino]],<ref>{{cite news |url= http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/columns/phong-luu/TMG9082454/Meet-Adam-Senn-the-new-face-of-Dolce-and-Gabbanas-The-One-Sport.html |title= Meet Adam Senn, the new face of Dolce & Gabbana's The One Sport |date=15 February 2012 |author=Phong Luu |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Giuseppe Tornatore, and [[Mariano Vivanco]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.papermag.com/2012/05/why_is_this_dolce_gabanna_post.php |title= Why Is This Dolce & Gabbana Poster Worth $500? |author=Gary Pini |date=7 May 2012 |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana have won two Leadawards for their campaigns from Germany's leading advertising awards. In 2004 they won for their Fall/Winter 2003/04 campaign<ref>{{cite web |url= http://leadacademy.de/2004/preistraeger.html |title=The Winners |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref> and in 2006 they won for their Fall/Winter 2005/06 campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://leadacademy.de/2006/preistraeger.html |title=The Winners |accessdate=29 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Inspirations and style ==\n[[File:Dolce & Gabbana Shop (Via della Spiga - Milan) 02.jpg|thumb|The Dolce & Gabbana store of [[Via della Spiga]] in [[Milan]]]]\nOriginally inspired by eclectic, [[thrift shop]] [[bohemian]] style, Dolce & Gabbana's deeply colored, [[animal print]]s have been described as \"haute hippy dom\" taking inspiration in particular from Italy's prestigious film history. \"When we design it's like a movie (Domenico),\" says Domenico Dolce. \"We think of a story and we design the clothes to go with it (Domenico).\" They claim to be more concerned about creating the best, most flattering clothes than sparking trends, once admitting that they wouldn't mind if their only contribution to fashion history was a black bra (Dolce & Gabbana 2007). [[Sicily]] and [[Sicilian culture]] is the most important style and identity of Dolce & Gabbana.\n\nD & G trademarks include [[underwear-as-outerwear]] (such as corsets and bra fastenings), gangster boss [[pinstripe]] suits, and extravagantly printed coats. Meanwhile, their feminine collections are always backed by powerful ad campaigns, like the black-and-white ads featuring model Marpessa photographed by Ferdinando Scianna in 1987 (Dolce & Gabbana). \"They find their way out of any black dress, any buttoned-up blouse (Domenico),\" says Rossellini. \"The first piece of theirs I wore was a white shirt, very chaste, but cut to make my breasts look as if they were bursting out of it (Domenico).\"\n\nOnce dubbed the \"Gilbert and George of Italian fashion\",<ref name=AAA>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/spy/biographies/dolce-and-gabbana-biography |title=Dolce & Gabbana |author=Jo Craven |date=11 May 2011 |work=Vogue UK |accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana gave their fashion interests a musical turn in 1996, by recording their own single, in which they intoned the words \"D&G is love\" over a techno beat (Dolce & Gabbana 2011). Newer to the design game than other heavyweight Italian fashion houses such as [[Armani]] and [[Versace]], the pair acknowledge that luck has played its part in their phenomenal success. By 1997, their company reported a turnover of \u20ac400 million, prompting both designers to announce that they planned to retire by the age of 40 \u2013 a promise they did not keep (Domenico).\n\nAfter the designers spotted a Veneziano painting of Christ on the cross wearing a pair of their branded underwear briefs in the Venice Biennale, they commissioned the artist to do a portrait of them with the Madonna portrayed as the likeness of the chanteuse and performer [[Madonna Ciccone]] and the courtiers as two putti at her feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/758548c8-5d54-11e1-889d-00144feabdc0.html|title=Lunch with the FT: Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana|work=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.10magazine.com/article/15176531624/dolce-gabbana-art-house|title=10 Magazine|work=10magazine.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, the company launched a high-end fashion range aimed at wealthy Muslim women featuring a collection of hijabs and abayas printed with daisies, lemons and roses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/07/dolce-gabbana-debuts-luxury-hijab-collection|title=Dolce & Gabbana launches luxury hijab collection|last=Gani|first=Aisha|date=7 January 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|issn=0261-3077|accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\nIn addition to designing clothing, Dolce & Gabbana have co-authored nearly two dozen books featuring photographic narratives as well as collections of their own work. The proceeds of many of these books go to charities including the Children\u2019s Action Network and the Butterfly Onlus \"\u00e9cole sans fronti\u00e8res\" Foundation.<ref name=DGGH /> The following is a bibliography of their literary works:\n\n* ''10 Anni Dolce & Gabbana'' (A collection of the most important advertising and editorial images of the design house's first decade)<ref>{{cite book |title=10 Anni Dolce & Gabbana |year=1996 |publisher=Leonardo Arte SRL |author=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Wildness''<ref>{{cite book |title=Dolce & Gabbana Wildness |year=1997 |publisher=Leonardo Arte SRL |author=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Animal''<ref>{{cite book |title=Animal |author=Dolce & Gabbana |year=1998 |publisher=Abbeville Press}}</ref>\n* ''Hollywood'' (Features over 100 photographs of the movie stars from the post-1985 era)<ref>{{cite book |title=Hollywood |year=2003 |publisher=Assouline |author=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Calcio'' (Photographs of 44 soccer players, 3 teams, and 2 coaches)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marianovivanco.com/biography/ |title=Mariano Vivanco |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514225930/http://www.marianovivanco.com/biography/ |archivedate=14 May 2012 }}</ref>\n* ''A.C. Milan''<ref>{{cite book |title=AC Milan Dressed by Dolce & Gabbana |author=Dolce & Gabbana and Mariano Vivanco |year=2004 |publisher=Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref>\n* ''Music'' (Features over 150 of globally recognised musicians)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbana.it/books/ |title=Books |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''20 Years Dolce & Gabbana'' (A chronological photographic history of each of the house's collections, using over 1000 photos)<ref name=DGGH>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/corporate/en/history/main-stages.html |title=Group History |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Milan''<ref>{{cite book |title=Milan |author=Dolce & Gabbana and Mariano Vivanco |publisher=Mondadori Electa |year=2006}}</ref>\n* ''2006 Italia'' (A book celebrating the 2006 World Cup title won by Italy)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/books/nazionale/ |accessdate=30 May 2012 |title=2006 Italia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721140640/http://www.dolcegabbana.com/books/nazionale/ |archivedate=21 July 2011 }}</ref>\n* ''Fashion Album'' (Contains over 400 images paying homage to the great fashion photographers of Dolce & Gabbana collections)<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashion Album |author=Dolce & Gabbana and Mariuccia Casadio |publisher=Skira |year=2006}}</ref>\n* ''Secret Ceremony''<ref>{{cite book |title=Secret Ceremony |author=Steven Klein and Dolce & Gabbana |year=2007 |publisher=Dolce & Gabbana SRL}}</ref>\n* ''Family'' (A book that focuses on the family as the center of a man's life)<ref name=DGGH />\n* ''The Good Shepherd'' (A book that illustrates the day of a common shephard, wearing Dolce & Gabbana clothing)<ref>{{cite book |title=The Good Shepherd |author=Michael Roberts |year=2007 |publisher=Dolce & Gabbana SRL}}</ref>\n* ''Milano Beach Soccer''<ref name=DGGH />\n* ''Diamonds & Pearls''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.luxist.com/2008/12/26/dolce-and-gabbanas-i-diamonds-and-pearls-i/ |title=Dolce & Gabbana's Diamonds & Pearls |date=26 December 2008 |publisher=The Luxist |author=Jared Paul Stern |accessdate=30 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111223170044/http://www.luxist.com/2008/12/26/dolce-and-gabbanas-i-diamonds-and-pearls-i/ |archivedate=23 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''20 Years of Dolce & Gabbana for Men''<ref>{{cite book |title=20 Years of Dolce & Gabbana for Men |year=2010 |publisher=Mondadori Electa}}</ref>\n* ''Icons 1990\u20132010''<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.2dmblogazine.it/2011/06/icons-dolce-gabbana-1990-2010/ |title=Icons: Dolce & Gabbana 1990\u20132010 |date=1 June 2011 |publisher=2DM |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''Fashion Shows 1990 \u2013 2010''<ref>{{cite book |title=Fashion Shows 1990 \u2013 2010 Dolce & Gabbana |publisher=Mondadori Electa |year=2011}}</ref>\n* ''Nazionale Italiana: South Africa 2010'' (A series of images starring the Italian National Football Team during the training sessions preceding the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]])<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/features_fashion/2010/05/world-cup-in-south-africa-puts-soccer-and-fashion-on-the-same-team.html |title=\"Sporno\" Soccer studs pitch Fashion or Futball? |author=Rod Hagwood |date=27 May 2010 |work=[[Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel]] |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530230124/http://blogs.sun-sentinel.com/features_fashion/2010/05/world-cup-in-south-africa-puts-soccer-and-fashion-on-the-same-team.html |archivedate=30 May 2012 }}</ref>\n* ''Uomini''<ref>{{cite book |title=Uomini |year=2011 |publisher=Rizzoli |author=Mariano Vivanco and Dolce & Gabbana}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2011/01/06/dolce-and-gabbana-coffee-table-book-uomini |work=[[Vogue UK]] |author=Lauren Milligan |title=Dolce Undressed |date=6 January 2011}}</ref>\n* ''Milan Fashion Soccer Players Portraits''<ref>{{cite news |url= http://daman.co.id/dolce-gabbana-celebrates-ac-milan/ |title= Dolce & Gabbana celebrates AC MILAN |date=24 August 2011 |work=DA Man |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n* ''David Gandy'' (A 280-page photographic coffee table book of images chronicling collaborations with British model [[David Gandy]] from 2006 to 2011)<ref>{{cite book |title=David Gandy |author=Dolce & Gabbana |year=2011 |publisher=Rizzoli}}</ref>\n* ''Campioni''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.it/dg/books/campioni/ |title=''Campioni'' |accessdate=3 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Spaces and exhibitions ==\nDolce & Gabbana opened the ''La sede di via San Damiano'' [[atelier]] in September 1995. They opened a combined seven-floor boutique and corporate space ''Lo showroom di via Goldoni'' in 2002, moving from its prior main showroom at Piazza Umanitaria. In July 2006 Dolce & Gabbana then opened a 5,000 square foot show floor ''Lo showroom di via Broggi'' in Milan. The design house also bought the ''Il Metropol'' theatre in Milan, a historic cinema built in the 1940s. It was renovated and reopened in September 2005.<ref name=DGGH /> In 2006 Dolce & Gabbana opened IL GOLD, an establishment with caf\u00e9, bar, bistro, and restaurant areas. This is followed by the opening of a co-sponsored drinking establishment the duo founded at their Milanese men's showroom called the [[Martini (vermouth)|Martini Bar]] in 2003.<ref name=VGP /> An additional Martini Bar was later opened at their Shanghai showroom in 2006.<ref name=DGGH /> In 2009 Dolce & Gabbana had 93 boutiques and 11 factory outlets, and was sold in over 80 countries.<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=FEh-FZbsHRoC&pg=PT284&dq=dolce+and+Gabbana+number+of+stores#v=onepage&q=dolce%20and%20Gabbana%20number%20of%20stores&f=false |title= Plunkett's Retail Industry Almanac 2009: Retail Industry Market Research, Statistics, Trends and Leading Companies |author=Jack W. Plunkett |publisher=Plunkett Research |year=2008|isbn= 9781593921392 }}</ref> In all they have 251 mono-brand stores.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dolcegabbana.com/corporate/en/group/profile.html |accessdate=29 May 2012 |title=Group Profile}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States standalone boutiques can be found in [[Bal Harbour]], [[Beverly Hills]], Chicago, [[Houston]], [[Las Vegas]], and New York City. Dolce & Gabbana also operates boutiques in other cities in select department stores: [[Nordstrom]], [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[Neiman Marcus]], and [[Bergdorf Goodman]].\n\nIn addition to developing runway shows and advertising campaigns for its collections, Dolce & Gabbana use their spaces to host photography and other [[art exhibition]]s. Soon after the opening of the Il Metropol, they hosted two exhibitions by artist [[Ron Arad (industrial designer)|Ron Arad]] in the lobby space: ''Blo-Glo'' between April 2006 and April 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/en/events/bloglo_by_ron_arad |title=Blo-Glo by Ron Arad |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> and ''Bodyguards'' in late April 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/en/events/ |title=Bodyguards by Ron Arad |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> They held photography exhibitions featuring the work of [[Enzo Sellerio]] in 2007<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/it/events/fermo_immagine_fotografie_di_enzo_sellerio |title=Freeze: Photos by Enzo Sellerio |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> and [[Herbert List]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbanametropol.com/en/events/herbert_list_lo_sguardo_sulla_bellezza_an_eye_for_beauty_ |title=Herbert List: An Eye for Beauty |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> In 2011 Dolce & Gabbana held an open house and architectural exhibition with Studio Piuarch showcasing the studio's various architectural designs and projects since 1996.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hauteliving.com/2011/04/haute-event-dolce-gabbana-and-studio-piuarch-present-open-house-piuarchdolcegabbana/ |work=Haute Living |accessdate=19 May 2012 |title= Haute Event: Dolce & Gabbana and Studio Piuarch Present Open House \u2013 Piuarch@Dolce&Gabbana |author=Pauline Sung |date=11 April 2011}}</ref> Studio Piuarch built the Dolce & Gabbana headquarters in 2006, which was where the exhibition and open house was held.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.archdaily.com/2458/dolce-gabbana-headquarters-studio-piuarch/ |author=Nico Saieh |title=Dolce & Gabbana Headquarters / Studio Piuarch |date=16 June 2008 |accessdate=19 May 2012 |work=ArchDaily}}</ref>\n\nDolce & Gabbana also uses its spaces for book launches and photographic exhibitions of its own clothing, such as the book launch of their book ''David Gandy'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.style.it/moda/photogallery/protagonisti-ed-eventi/2011/06/20/dolcegabbana-e-david-gandy.aspx |title=Dolce & Gabbana Celebrates with David Gandy |date=20 June 2011 |author=Carolina Rimondi |work=Style.it |accessdate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824052603/http://www.style.it/moda/photogallery/protagonisti-ed-eventi/2011/06/20/dolcegabbana-e-david-gandy.aspx |archivedate=24 August 2011 }}</ref> They also use other spaces as well, such as the [[Palazzo della Ragione, Milan|Palazzo della Ragione in Milan]], where in May 2009 they staged a photographic exhibition of over 100 images selected from the history of [[Vogue (magazine)|US Vogue]] over its 90-year history. The exhibition was called ''Extreme Beauty in Vogue''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dolcegabbana.com/extreme-beauty-in-vogue/ |title= Extreme Beauty in Vogue |accessdate= 19 May 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120516185919/http://www.dolcegabbana.com/extreme-beauty-in-vogue/ |archivedate= 16 May 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.style.com/peopleparties/parties/scoop/fashionweek-030209_Dolce_Gabbana_Extreme_Beauty/ |title=To the Extreme |accessdate=19 May 2012 |year=2009 |author=Tim Blanks |work=Style.com}}</ref>\n\nThe company has production factories in [[Legnano]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.modemonline.com/fashion/mini-web-sites/fashion-brands/references/maurogasperi |title=Mauro Gasperi |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> and [[Incisa in Val d'Arno]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ymag.it/schede.asp?id=9270 |title= what's up in viapiranesi |date= 14 April 2011 |accessdate= 19 May 2012 |work= Ymag |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111204044424/http://www.ymag.it/schede.asp?id=9270 |archivedate= 4 December 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nDolce & Gabbana has been involved in many controversial cases, with accusations mainly related with [[racism]], [[sexism]] and [[homophobia]].<ref>[https://www.out.com/popnography/2018/11/21/brief-history-dolce-gabbana-being-racist-sexist-and-homophobic A Brief History of Dolce & Gabbana Being Racist, Sexist and Homophobic]</ref><ref>[https://www.dircksey.com.au/2017/07/dolce-and-gabbanah-the-casual-acceptance-of-racism-sexism-hate-speech-and-more-in-the-name-of-fashion/ Dolce and GabbaNAH: The casual acceptance of racism, sexism, hate speech and more in the name of \u2018fashion\u2019]</ref>\n=== Advertising ===\n[[File:1 dolce gabbana.jpg|thumb|2007 D&G advertising image subject to controversy.]]\n\nDolce & Gabbana was publicly criticised by Britain's advertising watchdog [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority (ASA)]] in January 2007, for an advertising campaign showing models brandishing knives.\n\nFollowing complaints from consumer groups in February 2007, Dolce & Gabbana pulled an advertisement in Spain that showed a man holding a woman to the ground by her wrists while a group of men look on. Spain's Labour and Social Affairs Ministry branded the campaign as illegal and humiliating to women, saying the woman's body position had no relation to the products Dolce & Gabbana was trying to sell.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.eitb24.com/new/en/B24_36294/life/MILAN-BASED-FASHION-HOUSE-Dolce-Gabbana-angry-at/ | title = Dolce & Gabbana angry at advertising campaign controversy in Spain | work = Euskal Irrati Telebista | date = 23 February 2007 | accessdate =24 February 2007}}</ref> Italian publications followed suit, banning the ad. This advertisement was called \"a glorification of [[gang rape]]\" and declared \"one of the most controversial advertisements in fashion history\" by ''[[Debonair Magazine (U.S.)|Debonair Magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Most Controversial Ads in Fashion History|url=http://www.debonairmag.com/the-most-controversial-ads-in-fashion-history/7|accessdate=24 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123220310/http://www.debonairmag.com/the-most-controversial-ads-in-fashion-history/7|archive-date=23 November 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> When asked about the ad being banned in Spain, Dolce & Gabbana responded that the \"Spaniards were a bit backward.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://nextshark.com/people-are-pissed-at-dolce-gabbana-again-for-these-ads-depicting-gang-rape/|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150321012450/http://nextshark.com/people-are-pissed-at-dolce-gabbana-again-for-these-ads-depicting-gang-rape/|url-status = dead|archivedate = 21 March 2015|title = People Are Pissed at Dolce & Gabbana Again For These Ads Depicting Gang Rape|date = 18 March 2015|accessdate = 14 October 2015|website = NextShark|last = Chan|first = Augustine Reyes}}</ref> According to the Daily Mail, Dolce & Gabbana's ad was said to \"offend the dignity of the woman.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThis particular ad was brought up again seven years later by Kelly Cutrone, a well-known fashion publicist, when she mentioned it on her Twitter account. According to Nextshark.com, \"she slammed Dolce & Gabbana, claiming the ad, which depicts a woman being pinned to the group by a half-naked man as three men look on, simulates a 'gang bang'.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> According to ''The Huffington Post UK'', feminist writer Louise Pennington recently also commented on the image. She stated that, \"This particular image is a representative of an increasingly misogynistic contraction of women in the fashion industry demonstrating very clear links between the fashion-beauty industry and the mainstreaming of pornography. Those who suggest this image is harmless fail to recognize the reality of rape culture and the dehumanization of women's bodies in our pornographic mainstream media.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/03/18/dolce-and-gabbana0gang-rape-advert_n_6893044.html|title = 'Gang Rape' Dolce & Gabbana Advert Brings Yet More Controversy For Brand After 'Synthetic' IVF Comments|date = 18 March 2015|accessdate = 16 November 2015|website = The Huffington Post UK|last = Moss|first = Rachel}}</ref>\n\n=== Hong Kong photo ban ===\n[[File:D&G Hong Kong Racism.jpg|thumb|One of the four streets blocked during the Sunday protest.]]\n\nOn 5 January 2012, ''[[Apple Daily]]'' reported that only Hong Kong residents (and not mainland Chinese or foreigners) had been prevented from taking pictures of Dolce & Gabbana window displays in both their Hong Kong stores, stirring [[Hong Kong-Mainland conflict|anti-Mainland Chinese sentiment]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/template/apple/art_main.php?iss_id=20120105&sec_id=4104&art_id=15954668&av_id=15955030 | title=\u64c5\u7981\u9014\u4eba\u62cd\u7167\u3000\u73b7\u6c61\u8cfc\u7269\u5929\u5802 \u540d\u5e97\u60e1\u9738 D&G |language=Chinese |trans-title= D&G the Tyrannical Luxury Shop Unpermittedly Forbids By-passers to Take Photos, \"Shoppers' Paradise\" Ashamed |work=Apple Daily |location=Hong Kong | date=5 January 2012 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | author=\u6881\u5fa1\u548c\u3001\u76e7\u52c1\u696d\u3001\u4f0d\u96c5\u8b19}}</ref> In particular staff and security personnel at their flagship store on [[Canton Road]] asserted the pavement area outside was private property where photography was forbidden. The actions sparked protests spanning several days and gained international news coverage on 8 January.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/business/protest-at-dolce-and-gabbana-store-in-hong-kong-follows-alleged-ban-on-photography/story-e6frfm1i-1226239375370#ixzz1irefM2CG | title=Protest at Dolce and Gabbana store in Hong Kong follows alleged ban on photography | work=[[News Limited]] Australia|date= 8 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/BreakingNews/SEAsia/Story/STIStory_753234.html | title=Hundreds protest D&G photo 'ban' in Hong Kong |work=The Sunday Times |location=UK|date= 8 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/hongkong/9001001/One-thousand-protest-Dolce-and-Gabbana-Hong-Kong-store-over-photo-ban.html | title=One thousand protest Dolce & Gabbana Hong Kong store over photo ban |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date= 9 January 2012|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/scene/2012/01/09/dolce-gabbana-photo-ban-sparks-protest/ | title=Dolce & Gabbana Photo Ban Sparks Protest|work=The Wall Street Journal|date= 9 January 2012|accessdate=9 January 2012}}</ref> Citing the case of Zhou Jiugeng, a Nanjing official whose high-living lifestyle was identified by mainland Chinese internet users using photographs, local news reports speculated that the Dolce & Gabbana photo ban may have been imposed at the request of some wealthy Chinese government officials attempting to block details on the source of their wealth.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20120108/00176_006.html | title=D&G\u4e8b\u4ef6\u8d77\u56e0 \u50b3\u5167\u5730\u9ad8\u5e79\u6295\u8a34 \u6015\u88ab\u626f\u4e0a\u8caa\u6c61|trans-title= Alleged Cause of D&G Incident: Fear of Corruption <nowiki>[</nowiki>Accusations<nowiki>]</nowiki>, Mainland Officials Complain| work=Oriental Daily|date= 8 January 2012|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/4026624/Chinese-internet-vigilantes-bring-down-another-official.html|title=Chinese internet vigilantes bring down another official|author=Malcolm Moore in Shanghai|date=30 December 2008|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nDolce & Gabbana finally issued a formal apology to the people of Hong Kong from its Milan headquarters on 18 January 2012.<ref>[http://www.am730.com.hk/article.php?article=89703&d=1670 D&G\u51cc\u6668\u300c\u9053\u6b49\u300d \u7db2\u6c11\u62d2\u6536\u300c\u884c\u8ca8\u300d]\uff0cAM730\uff0c19 January 2012</ref><ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2012/01/19/dolce-gabbana-apologizes-for-photo-spat/ Dolce & Gabbana Apologizes for Photo Spat], Wall Street Journal, 19 January 2012</ref>\n\n=== Gay adoption and in vitro fertilization ===\nIn an interview in 16 March 2015 issue of Italian magazine [[Panorama (magazine)|Panorama]], Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce caused controversy when they remarked, \"We oppose gay adoptions. The only family is the traditional one.\" They also criticized [[in vitro fertilisation]] (IVF) and [[surrogacy]] by saying, \"No chemical offspring and rented uterus: life has a natural flow, there are things that should not be changed.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.panorama.it/news/cronaca/dolce-gabbana-lunica-famiglia-quella-tradizionale/ | publisher=Panorama | title=Figli e famiglia, la verit\u00e0 di Dolce e Gabbana | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> Since the comments were made by two gay men in an industry often seen as gay-friendly, reactions were especially harsh.\n\nCritics took to social media to voice their opposition, with the hashtag #BoycottDolceGabbana garnering 30,000 tweets on Twitter in five days. Celebrities, including Elton John, Madonna, Victoria Beckham, Ricky Martin, Martina Navratilova and Courtney Love, were among those expressing anger over the remarks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/15/elton-john-boycott-dolce-gabbana-synthetic-ivf-babies-comment|title=Elton John: boycott Dolce & Gabbana over 'synthetic' IVF babies comment|last=Association|first=Press|date=2015-03-15|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Love said she would \"burn all of her Dolce and Gabbana clothing\", while John, father of two children conceived through IVF, commented, \"How dare you refer to my beautiful children as 'synthetic'. And shame on you for wagging your judgmental little fingers at IVF \u2013 a miracle that has allowed legions of loving people, both straight and gay, to fulfil their dream of having children.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-31907007 | newspaper=BBC | title=Dolce and Gabbana say 'Boycott Elton John' | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> In an Instagram post Madonna, who appeared in a 2010 Dolce & Gabbana campaign, said, \"All babies contain a soul however they come to this earth and their families. There is nothing synthetic about a soul!! So how can we dismiss IVF and surrogacy? Every soul comes to us to teach us a lesson. God has his hand in everything even technology! We are arrogant to think Man does anything on his own. As above so below! Think before you speak.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/19/madonna-dolce-gabbana_n_6901330.html | newspaper=Huffington Post | title=Madonna Responds To The Dolce & Gabbana Controversy | first=Cavan |last=Sieczkowski | date=19 March 2015 | accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nMore than 10,000 people signed an online petition calling for Macy's and Debenhams to stop stocking the brand in their department stores, until D&G retracted their statements and apologized. Protesters also gathered outside Dolce & Gabbana\u2019s flagship London shop calling for an international boycott of the luxury fashion store.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2015/mar/19/dolce-gabbana-london-protests-boycott-shop | newspaper=The Guardian | title=Dolce & Gabbana protesters demand boycott outside London shop | first=Aisha | last=Gani | date=19 March 2015 | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nDolce & Gabbana criticized calls for a boycott on their brand as \"medieval\" and called for fans to use the hashtag #BoycottEltonJohn, though it resulted in only 1,500 tweets.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-31907007 |newspaper=BBC News| title=Dolce and Gabbana say 'Boycott Elton John'| date=16 March 2015| accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref> After being asked during an interview with CNN if he supported having children through IVF, Dolce replied, \"Yeah, I don't have anything bad, because the beauty of the world is freedom...We love gay couple. We are gay. We love gay couple. We love gay adoption. We love everything. It's just an express of my private point of view.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/03/18/world/dolce-gabbana-ivf/| newspaper=CNN| title=CNN Exclusive: Dolce & Gabbana: We don't judge on IVF| first=Anna Coren |last=Madison Park|date= 18 March 2015| accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/dolce--gabbana-slam-boycott-5359770 |newspaper=Daily Mirror | title=Dolce & Gabbana slam boycott campaign over IVF and adoption row as 'medieval' | first=Charlotte | last=Wareing |date=18 March 2015 | accessdate=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Shanghai event promotion video ===\n[[File:D&G Using Chopsticks to Eat Italian Foods.png|thumb|200px|The first video lectures the lady should use ''this stick shaped silverware like pliers'' to eat pizza. Episode 1: ''Pizza Margherita'']]\nIn November 2018, Dolce & Gabbana released a series of videos on [[Instagram]], [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]] profiles, as well as its [[Sina Weibo]] account in China, featuring a Chinese model with her eye intentionally narrowed <ref>{{cite web |title=DG\u8fb1\u534e\u5e7f\u544a\u6a21\u7279\u5de6\u4e5f\u6545\u610f\u5316\u5986\u5c0f\u773c\uff1f\u5de6\u4e5f\u5e94\u8be5\u4e3a\u89c6\u9891\u9053\u6b49\u5417\uff1f|trans-title= Model Zuo Ye from D&G Chinese insulting commercial has been intentionally shrinked her eyes? Should she apologize for the video?|url=http://www.hxnews.com/news/yule/201811/24/1657224.shtml|website=\u6d77\u5ce1\u7f51|date=24 November 2018|accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>, dressed up in the brand's garments and accessories and clumsily attempting to use [[chopstick]]s to eat Italian food in a pretentious way. The video narratage is in [[Standard Mandarin]] with a hubristic and lecturing tone, while having [[sexual suggestiveness|sexually suggestive]] lines.<ref>{{cite web |title=D&G\u4e8b\u4ef6\uff1a\u5f53\u4e1c\u65b9\u4e0d\u518d\u63a5\u53d7\u897f\u65b9\u7684\u5ba1\u7f8e\"\u9a6f\u5316\" |trans-title= When the East is no longer accepting the 'acclimatization' of the Western views of beauty|url=https://wallstreetcn.com/articles/3442931 |website=Wall Street China|date=24 November 2018 |accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=D&G\uff1a\"\u81f4\u656c\u4e2d\u56fd\"\u4e3a\u4f55\u641e\u7838\uff1f|trans-title= Why 'In honor of China' is screwed up?|url=http://www.ftchinese.com/story/001080350?full=y&archive |website=FT Chinese |date=23 November 2018|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> These videos were intended to promote \"The Great Show\", a catwalk event to be held at Expo Center of [[Shanghai]], [[China]] on 21 November. Social media users commented that it reflects Dolce & Gabbana's lack of understanding of Chinese culture and [[racism]]. Under the public pressure, D&G removed this series from its Sina Weibo whilst still keeping them on Instagram.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/dolce-gabbana-faces-blacklash-china-racist-ads-remarks-instagram-170723228.html|title=Dolce & Gabbana faces backlash in China over 'racist' ads and remarks on Instagram and Youtube|last=Hu|first=Krystal|date=21 November 2018|publisher=Yahoo! Finance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121214516/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/dolce-gabbana-faces-blacklash-china-racist-ads-remarks-instagram-170723228.html|archivedate=21 November 2018|url-status=dead|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref> Social media outcry was further exacerbated by a screen capture of racist comments alleged to have been made by D&G co-founder, Stefano Gabbana, in a direct message on Instagram to an American fashion blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/chinese-model-thought-career-was-over-after-racist-dolce-and-gabbana-ad|title=Chinese model thought career was over after 'racist' Dolce and Gabbana ad|website=SBS News|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref> Stefano Gabbana complained about removing the videos from the internet and called China the \"Ignorant Dirty Smelling Mafia\", adding that it was a \"country of shit\" in the message.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/5462653/dolce-gabbana-apology-insensitive-china-ads/|title=Dolce & Gabbana Issues Apology to China After Backlash Over Ads|last=Martinez|first=Gina|date=24 November 2018|website=Time|accessdate=25 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-11-24/dolce-&-gabbana-founders-apologise-for-china-racism-incident/10551342|title=Dolce & Gabbana apologises over China racism furore|date=2018-11-24|website=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2174382/celebrities-and-models-boycott-dolce-and-gabbana-show-china-over|title=Celebrities boycott Dolce & Gabbana show in China over 'racist outburst'|date=2018-11-21|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref> Later Dolce & Gabbana claimed on Instagram that both the brand's and the designer's accounts had been hacked. [[Wang Junkai]] and [[Dilraba Dilmurat]], both of whom served as the brand's celebrity ambassadors, severed their ties with the company. Other celebrities, including [[Zhang Ziyi]], [[Li Bingbing]] and [[Chen Kun]] withdrew from the event. Ultimately, the show was cancelled by the brand.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/11/20/dolce-and-gabbana-accused-of-racism-in-chinese-chopsticks-ads.html | newspaper=CNBC | title=Dolce and Gabbana reportedly cancels Shanghai fashion show after racism accusations | last=Handley | first=Lucy | date=20 November 2018 | accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.scmp.com/magazines/style/fashion-beauty/article/2174362/dolce-gabbanas-shanghai-show-cancelled-amid | newspaper=South China Morning Post | title=Dolce & Gabbana's Shanghai show is cancelled amid accusations of racism in 'Chinese chopsticks' ad campaign |  last=Liu | first=Leona | date=21 November 2018 | accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/dolce-gabbana-shanghai-controversy/index.html | newspaper=CNN | title=Dolce & Gabbana cancels China show amid 'racist' ad controversy | last=Chung | first=Stephy| last2=Holland | first2=Oscar  | date=21 November 2018 | accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/society/article/2174675/dolce-gabbana-founders-ask-chinese-people-forgiveness-after|title=Dolce & Gabbana founders beg Chinese people\u2019s forgiveness|date=2018-11-23|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\nChinese e-commerce sites, including [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]] and [[JD.com]], removed the products of Dolce & Gabbana.<ref name=wp201811>{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinese-campaign-to-boycott-dolce-and-gabbana-mounts-as-co-founders-issue-apology/2018/11/23/2ff1e69e-ef07-11e8-9236-bb94154151d2_story.html?noredirect=on | newspaper=The Washington Post | title=Chinese campaign to boycott Dolce & Gabbana mounts as co-founders issue apology | last=Shin | first=Gerry  | date=23 November 2018 | accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref> The founders of Dolce & Gabbana apologized in a video on 23 November, which was posted on its Sina Weibo account, and also posted on Instagram and Facebook later. Throughout the video, the founders can be seen reading off a script from a teleprompter located on the right. At the end of the video, the founders were saying \"\u5bf9\u4e0d\u8d77\" (sorry) in Chinese. Meanwhile, the three videos were finally removed from the official Instagram account.<ref name=wp201811/><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/dolce-gabbana-founders-make-video-apology-china-after-racism-accusations-n939461| publisher=NBC News | title=Dolce & Gabbana founders make video apology to China after racism accusations | date=23 November 2018 | accessdate=24 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-46968750|title=Model reveals pain of 'racist' D&G ad|date=2019-01-23|access-date=2019-08-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Other ===\n\nIn their Spring/Summer 2013 collection they included earrings and fabric prints that to American audiences closely resembled imagery associated with the [[Mammy archetype]] with many media outlets commenting the likeness. The designs, however, were intended to make reference to Sicilian Moor's heads, popular good luck charms in Sicilian folklore.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://jezebel.com/5946724/dolce--gabbana-shows-racist-mammy-earrings-and-fun-fabric-prints | newspaper=Jezebel | title=Dolce & Gabbana Shows Racist 'Mammy' Earrings and Fabric Prints | first=Jenna | last=Sauers | date=27 September 2012 | accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2016, the brand came under fire for a listing on their web store of a pair of sandals featuring colorful decorations and pom poms with the title of \"Slave Sandal in Napa Leather\". Other retailers listed them as the Bianca or the Pom Pom sandal. Sandals in Italy are often referred to as such in reference to Ancient Rome. When social media users called the name into question, the listing was changed.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/fashion/dolce-gabbana-release-offensive-slave-sandal-article-1.2551821 | newspaper=New York Daily News | title=Dolce & Gabbana release offensive 'Slave Sandal' as part of Spring 2016 collection | first=Nicole | last=Bitette | date=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Legal issues ==\n\nIn May 2009, the [[Italian government]] charged Dolce & Gabbana with [[tax evasion]] for having moved assets of about 249 million euros to [[Luxembourg]] in the 2004\u20132006 period.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://mazzetta.splinder.com/post/20651674/Dolce+%26+Gabbana+tentano+l%27evas | title = D&G tentano l'evasione del secolo | work = Mazzetta blog | date = 31 May 2009 | accessdate = 31 May 2009 }}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ilgiornale.it/a.pic1?ID=353960 | title = Pi\u00f9 Gabbana che Dolce Perch\u00e9 i giornali ignorano quella notizia |work=Il Giornale |language=Italian | date = 26 May 2009 | accessdate =31 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2013, they were found guilty of failing to declare 1 billion euros ($1.3 billion) of income to authorities after moving their brand to [[Gado (company)|Gado]], a Luxembourg-based [[holding company]]. The court sentenced them both to one year and eight months in jail.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://business.time.com/2013/06/19/dolce-and-gabbana-convicted-of-tax-evasion/#ixzz2Wg0MuLJt | title = Dolce and Gabbana Convicted of Tax Evasion | work = Time | date = 19 June 2013 | accessdate = 19 June 2013 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130622063541/http://business.time.com/2013/06/19/dolce-and-gabbana-convicted-of-tax-evasion/#ixzz2Wg0MuLJt | archivedate = 22 June 2013 }}</ref> Dolce & Gabbana were quick to file a 90-page appeal and thus did not face any jail time.\n\nOn 30 April 2014, a three judge panel overruled the appeal and decided to uphold the initial sentence.<ref name=\"Dolce, Gabbana Found Guilty of Tax Evasion\">{{cite web | url=http://www.businessoffashion.com/2014/04/dolce-gabbana-appeal-denied-guilty-tax-evasion.html | title=Dolce, Gabbana Found Guilty of Tax Evasion | publisher=Business of Fashion | date=30 April 2014 | accessdate=7 May 2014 | author=Wang, Lisa}}</ref> However, since they were sentenced to only one year and six months, which is under the two-year minimum, both of them will not serve actual imprisonment in jail.<ref name=\"Dolce, Gabbana Found Guilty of Tax Evasion\"/>\n\nOn 24 October 2014, both Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana were found innocent of tax evasion by the [[Italian Court of Justice]].<ref name=\"Robert Wood\">{{cite news \n| last= Wood \n| first= Robert W. \n| url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/robertwood/2014/10/25/dolce-gabbana-cleared-of-tax-evasion-could-help-lionel-messi-trial/\n| title= Dolce & Gabbana Cleared Of Tax Evasion, Could Help Lionel Messi Trial\n| publisher= forbes.com\n| date= 25 October 2014\n| accessdate= \n}}</ref> After the court's decision was announced, Stefano Gabbana tweeted in Italian, \"We knew it!!! We are honest people!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/591768/dolce-gabbana-founders-found-innocent-in-tax-evasion-case-we-knew-it-we-are-honest-people|title=Dolce & Gabbana Founders Found Innocent in Tax Evasion Case |work=E! Online}}</ref><ref name=\"LUKE LEITCH\">{{cite news \n| last= LEITCH\n| first= LUKE \n| url= http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/news-features/TMG11186176/Dolce-and-Gabbana-cleared-of-tax-evasion.html\n| title= Dolce and Gabbana cleared of tax evasion: Rome's supreme court overturned a ruling that found designers Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana guilty of tax evasion with a 20-month prison penalty\n| publisher= telegraph.co.uk\n| date= 24 October 2014\n| accessdate= \n}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* \"Dolce & Gabbana.\" The Thames & Hudson Dictionary of Fashion and Fashion Designers. London: Thames & Hudson, 2007. Credo Reference. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"Gabbana, Stefano.\" Marquis Who's Who in the World. New Providence: Marquis Who's Who LLC, 2011. Credo Reference. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"Gabbana, Stefano.\" The Thames & Hudson Dictionary of Fashion and Fashion Designers. London: Thames & Hudson, 2007. Credo Reference. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"[http://www.swide.com/luxury-magazine/History/DG-Archive/domenico-dolce-quotes/2011/6/2 Domenico Dolce Quotes \u2013 Swide Magazine].\" Swide Magazine by Dolce&Gabbana. Swide Magazine, 2 June 2011. Web. 29 November 2011.\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20150227211103/http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biographies/dolce-gabbana.html Dolce & Gabbana \u2013 Biography on Bio].\" Bio: Shows, Video, TV Schedule and More on Bio. AETN UK. Web. 29 November 2011.\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Dolce & Gabbana}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.dolcegabbana.com/}}\n* {{Fashionlabel|id=dolce-gabbana}}\n* [https://www.fashion.net/dolce-gabbana Dolce & Gabbana on FASHION NET]\n<!--==========================({{NoMoreLinks}})============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA  |\n    | IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS NOR SHOULD IT BE USED FOR ADVERTISING. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    ===========================({{NoMoreLinks}})===========================-->\n\n{{Designer labels}}\n{{Men's undergarments}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolce and Gabbana}}\n[[Category:Dolce & Gabbana| ]]\n[[Category:Italian fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Clothing brands of Italy]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of Italy]]\n[[Cat